♪<i>♪ A month to remember ♪</i>

06:40.033 --> 06:42.806
♪<i>♪ A month to remember ♪</i>

06:42.939 --> 06:46.880
♪<i>♪ It's a magical feeling,
it's time for believing ♪</i>

06:47.014 --> 06:49.686
♪<i>♪ Better be ready, it's here ♪</i>

06:49.820 --> 06:52.759
♪<i>♪ Let's make December ♪</i>

06:52.893 --> 06:57.969
♪<i>♪ A month to remember ♪</i>

06:58.103 --> 07:02.511
♪<i>♪ Christmas, is the
best time of the year ♪</i>

07:07.487 --> 07:09.358
[Mary sighs] Hank.

07:09.760 --> 07:11.061
[ground squishes]

07:12.264 --> 07:13.132
Terrific.

07:14.603 --> 07:17.642
[mud splatters]

07:17.776 --> 07:21.115
[soft, bright music]

07:26.627 --> 07:27.829
May I help you?

07:27.962 --> 07:29.365
Yeah, just
checking in, please.

07:29.498 --> 07:30.834
Mary Romero.

07:31.569 --> 07:32.572
You know who I am?

07:32.706 --> 07:34.041
Oh, honey, this is Brunswick.

07:34.175 --> 07:36.412
Everybody knows who you
are and why you're here.

07:36.546 --> 07:38.115
I'd say I'm ready
for my close-up,

07:38.249 --> 07:40.788
but you must have heard
that joke a million times.

07:40.922 --> 07:42.424
Well, believe it or
not, most of the people

07:42.559 --> 07:44.194
I interview don't
wanna be on camera,

07:44.328 --> 07:46.065
especially if they're
being held accountable.

07:46.199 --> 07:47.033
Oh.

07:48.069 --> 07:50.240
I actually have two rooms
under your name, Ms. Romero.

07:50.373 --> 07:51.710
Is that correct?

07:51.844 --> 07:53.781
Yes, my cameraman, he'll
be joining me tomorrow.

07:53.914 --> 07:55.684
And we're looking
forward to having him.

07:55.818 --> 07:56.887
Great, thanks.

07:57.021 --> 07:58.624
You know,
I have to make a stop.

07:58.757 --> 08:00.694
- Do you know Alton Johnson?
- [Bernice chuckles]

08:00.828 --> 08:03.065
Let me guess, everybody
knows Alton Johnson.

08:03.199 --> 08:04.536
You catch on quick.

08:04.669 --> 08:06.205
Would you mind telling
me where the factory is?

08:06.339 --> 08:08.878
Come back the way you came,
take a left at the light.

08:09.011 --> 08:11.216
It's about a mile down,
you can't miss it.

08:11.349 --> 08:12.919
It's a factory.

08:13.052 --> 08:14.454
Right. Okay.

08:14.589 --> 08:17.494
We're really excited to
have you here, Ms. Romero.

08:17.629 --> 08:19.766
Please, just call me Mary.

08:19.899 --> 08:21.636
Mary, I'm Bernice.

08:21.770 --> 08:24.008
I do hope you enjoy our town.

08:24.141 --> 08:25.744
I'm sure I will.

08:30.755 --> 08:34.662
[bright, upbeat music]

08:50.326 --> 08:52.565
Eat your heart
out, Diane Sawyer.

08:55.638 --> 08:56.573
You must be--

08:56.706 --> 08:58.511
Mary Romero.

08:58.644 --> 08:59.513
[Alton chuckles]

08:59.646 --> 09:00.914
Wonderful to meet you.

09:01.048 --> 09:02.885
I can't tell you how
excited I am about this.

09:03.019 --> 09:04.956
Yeah, I was told that you were

09:05.089 --> 09:06.726
one of our most
important advertisers.

09:06.860 --> 09:07.996
I've gotten to know Hank Dean

09:08.129 --> 09:10.400
personally over the
years, good man.

09:10.534 --> 09:12.003
Yeah, and there they are.

09:12.137 --> 09:13.306
[Alton] <i>What do you think?</i>

09:13.440 --> 09:14.543
I can't believe it.

09:14.676 --> 09:16.178
Me neither, 40 years.

09:16.312 --> 09:17.848
But we can save that
for my interview.

09:17.982 --> 09:20.153
Let's go have a quick
chat in my office.

09:25.030 --> 09:26.567
I hope you'll excuse the mess.

09:26.700 --> 09:30.273
I never bought that business
about a cluttered mind.

09:30.406 --> 09:33.446
Well, a cluttered mind has
a lot of good stuff in it.

09:33.580 --> 09:35.483
These are your artifacts.

09:35.618 --> 09:36.920
My artifacts?

09:37.053 --> 09:38.823
Right, family photos,
old advertisements,

09:38.957 --> 09:40.528
product shots, stuff like that.

09:40.661 --> 09:42.565
Soon as you told me, I had
my assistant start looking.

09:42.698 --> 09:44.034
I hope that's enough.

09:44.168 --> 09:46.807
Your archive, and
yes, that is plenty.

09:46.940 --> 09:48.243
- Thank you.
- I'll have one of

09:48.376 --> 09:50.046
my delivery guys bring it
over to the inn for you.

09:50.179 --> 09:51.181
Okay.

09:51.315 --> 09:52.885
Now, how shall we begin?

09:53.019 --> 09:55.657
I have so many ideas I'd
love to share with you.

09:55.791 --> 09:56.826
Well, Mr. Johnson--

09:56.960 --> 09:58.563
Alton, please.

09:58.697 --> 10:00.300
It was good enough
for my parents.

10:00.433 --> 10:02.972
Alton, look, I know
that this isn't really

10:03.106 --> 10:04.609
a hard-hitting
investigative piece,

10:04.743 --> 10:06.145
but I would like to
approach it the same way

10:06.278 --> 10:07.715
that I do the rest
of my stories,

10:07.848 --> 10:09.786
which means conducting
my own research

10:09.920 --> 10:11.489
and building a rapport
with the interviewees.

10:11.623 --> 10:13.660
So, what you're telling
me is to keep my mouth shut

10:13.793 --> 10:15.062
and stay in my own
lane, is that it?

10:15.196 --> 10:17.200
[Mary chuckles]
I love your enthusiasm.

10:17.334 --> 10:18.837
<i>You don't have to
explain yourself.</i>

10:18.970 --> 10:20.608
This isn't the first
time I've been accused

10:20.741 --> 10:22.277
of being a bit too eager.

10:22.411 --> 10:26.118
The truth is, I'm just very
proud of what we built here.

10:26.252 --> 10:27.822
But you just tell
us what you need,

10:27.955 --> 10:29.225
we're all at your disposal.

10:29.358 --> 10:31.261
- Thank you, so much.
- [glass clanks]

10:31.395 --> 10:33.132
Sorry to bother you, Dad, but
they need you over in shipping.

10:33.266 --> 10:35.336
Blake, wait, I want you
to meet Mary Romero.

10:35.470 --> 10:36.906
<i>She's the
television reporter--</i>

10:37.040 --> 10:38.309
[Blake] <i>Yeah,
I know who she is.</i>

10:39.010 --> 10:40.982
[Mary] <i>Well, so much for
flying under the radar.</i>

10:41.349 --> 10:43.353
Seems like everyone already
knows who I am around here.

10:43.486 --> 10:46.058
Well, your reputation
precedes you.

10:47.962 --> 10:49.866
I'll be in the factory
if you need me.

10:53.005 --> 10:54.876
He did not seem
happy that I'm here.

10:55.009 --> 10:56.780
Oh, he'll come
around eventually.

10:56.913 --> 10:59.552
It's just that my
son wasn't exactly

10:59.685 --> 11:01.155
<i>enthusiastic about this piece.</i>

11:01.288 --> 11:04.161
In fact, to be honest, he
thought it was a bad idea.

11:04.294 --> 11:05.497
Really, why?

11:05.631 --> 11:07.134
[Hank] <i>Oh, he's worried
the story will be</i>

11:07.267 --> 11:10.741
about our success,
our commercial success.

11:10.874 --> 11:12.310
Blake's always
wanted the company

11:12.444 --> 11:13.947
<i>to be about more than
that, but you know what?</i>

11:14.080 --> 11:15.517
<i>Our products
make people happy,</i>

11:15.651 --> 11:17.420
which is something you'll
never hear me apologize for,

11:17.555 --> 11:19.225
and if our customer's
happiness has made us

11:19.358 --> 11:21.896
<i>a commercial success,
then who's fault that?</i>

11:22.030 --> 11:23.365
Well, sounds reasonable to me.

11:23.499 --> 11:26.540
But most importantly,
the Mistletoads.

11:26.673 --> 11:27.842
[Alton chuckles]

11:27.976 --> 11:29.745
Yes, I heard they
were quite popular.

11:29.879 --> 11:31.381
Oh, the kids couldn't
get enough of 'em.

11:31.516 --> 11:32.818
They just loved 'em.

11:32.952 --> 11:33.854
Most did, anyway.

11:33.987 --> 11:35.423
[Alton chuckles]

11:38.029 --> 11:39.799
And we can't have another
drive card expedited,

11:39.932 --> 11:41.102
even shipped overnight?

11:41.603 --> 11:44.140
We can, but we still lose
an entire 12-hour shift.

11:45.578 --> 11:47.013
[Blake sighs]

11:47.146 --> 11:50.120
Okay, let's move production
to Woodbury's plant,

11:50.253 --> 11:51.723
and let's add a night shift.

11:52.290 --> 11:53.727
I'm sure the crew
there will appreciate

11:53.861 --> 11:55.396
the overtime before
the holidays.

11:55.531 --> 11:56.533
I'm on it.

11:56.666 --> 11:58.202
Appreciate you.

12:01.041 --> 12:02.912
Ms. Romero, what
can I do for you?

12:03.045 --> 12:04.949
Were you serious
about my reputation?

12:05.082 --> 12:06.385
- Of course.
- Meaning what?

12:06.519 --> 12:08.456
Meaning, I'm familiar
with your work.

12:08.591 --> 12:09.458
Really?

12:09.592 --> 12:10.894
What specifically?

12:11.028 --> 12:12.531
Well, your piece
on Midwest Chem,

12:12.665 --> 12:14.636
dumping hazardous materials
into the Mississippi.

12:14.769 --> 12:16.606
It was very illuminating.

12:16.740 --> 12:17.942
You saw that?

12:18.677 --> 12:20.514
The Mississippi River
flows into the Iowa.

12:20.647 --> 12:24.021
Iowa flows into the Cedar,
which flows right into town.

12:24.155 --> 12:25.858
I'm sure we're best
known for Johnson Toys,

12:25.991 --> 12:27.929
but we're still a farming
community at heart.

12:28.062 --> 12:30.601
Right. You know, Alton said
you weren't too keen

12:30.735 --> 12:31.737
on talking to me.

12:31.870 --> 12:33.339
Well, I'm sure I can make

12:33.472 --> 12:35.778
a perfectly fine documentary
without my involvement.

12:35.911 --> 12:37.247
Without the grandson
of the founder,

12:37.381 --> 12:38.917
and the one next in line
to inherit the company?

12:39.051 --> 12:40.186
I don't think so.

12:40.319 --> 12:41.856
Sorry, but you're
gonna have to try.

12:41.990 --> 12:43.694
Why don't you wanna
be a part of the story?

12:43.827 --> 12:45.130
With all due respect,

12:45.263 --> 12:46.533
I can already see how
it's gonna turn out.

12:46.667 --> 12:47.969
Really?

12:48.102 --> 12:49.337
That's interesting,
because I'm producing it,

12:49.471 --> 12:51.576
and I don't even know
what the story is.

12:51.709 --> 12:52.845
Trust me.

12:53.613 --> 12:54.849
Indulge me.

12:54.982 --> 12:57.220
I don't know,
maybe something like,

12:58.256 --> 13:00.426
Johnson Toys is the
country's largest

13:00.560 --> 13:03.065
manufacturer of
everything Christmas.

13:03.198 --> 13:04.902
From America's
heartland, they produce

13:05.036 --> 13:07.074
literally thousands of items,

13:07.207 --> 13:10.045
from artificial trees
to advent calendars.

13:10.179 --> 13:12.317
But what they're best known for

13:12.451 --> 13:16.559
are there lovable Christmas
amphibians, the Mistletoads.

13:16.693 --> 13:19.030
Well, you could have
a future in showbiz.

13:19.164 --> 13:20.600
I think I'll leave
that up to you.

13:21.569 --> 13:23.273
Was I close?

13:23.406 --> 13:24.274
[Mary] <i>Sure.</i>

13:24.408 --> 13:25.844
Sure, that's what
my boss wants,

13:25.977 --> 13:27.514
that's probably what
your father wants.

13:27.648 --> 13:31.254
But I bet that there's a lot
more to the story than that.

13:32.357 --> 13:33.425
Okay.

13:33.994 --> 13:35.196
Follow me.

13:37.835 --> 13:41.075
[soft, bright music]

13:41.209 --> 13:45.518
[laughing voices softly echo]

13:45.651 --> 13:46.653
It's beautiful.

13:46.787 --> 13:48.890
My grandpa, Alton Johnson, Sr.

13:49.592 --> 13:51.763
[Mary] <i>Your
grandpa painted this?</i>

13:51.896 --> 13:53.299
<i>It's really good.</i>

13:53.432 --> 13:54.769
[Blake] <i>Yeah, and it
belongs in a museum,</i>

13:54.902 --> 13:56.506
not hanging on
some factory wall.

13:58.544 --> 14:00.012
So, show the world.

14:01.114 --> 14:02.818
Participate in the
story, and you can talk

14:02.951 --> 14:04.622
about your grandpa's
work all you want.

14:04.755 --> 14:05.758
[Blake chuckles]

14:05.892 --> 14:06.993
Think my dad will go for that?

14:07.127 --> 14:08.429
A little trip down memory lane,

14:08.563 --> 14:10.166
instead of the toys
that made him famous?

14:10.801 --> 14:13.506
I think you've got it
wrong how this works.

14:13.640 --> 14:16.913
Nobody has creative
control over my stories.

14:17.046 --> 14:19.952
Over your
advertiser-funded stories?

14:20.086 --> 14:21.556
The only reason I
took this assignment

14:21.690 --> 14:24.427
was because I was
promised creative control.

14:25.531 --> 14:27.066
You're pretty
good at what you do?

14:27.200 --> 14:28.537
I'm very good.

14:28.904 --> 14:31.408
Well, then you'll find a way
to tell the story without me.

14:32.444 --> 14:33.980
I'm gonna get you to say yes.

14:34.114 --> 14:35.951
Nice meeting you, Ms. Romero.

14:37.320 --> 14:39.190
You too, Mr. Johnson.

14:41.295 --> 14:44.568
[soft, bright music]

14:54.856 --> 14:56.125
Hey.

14:56.258 --> 14:57.928
Join me for some
hot chocolate?

14:58.061 --> 14:59.464
Um, no, thank you.

14:59.598 --> 15:01.101
I was just gonna head
out for some dinner.

15:01.234 --> 15:02.538
You know where you're going?

15:02.671 --> 15:04.976
No. No, I think I'm
just gonna walk into town

15:05.110 --> 15:06.445
and see what looks good.

15:06.580 --> 15:08.516
How was your visit
to the factory?

15:08.650 --> 15:10.052
It was interesting.

15:10.186 --> 15:11.923
You get to meet Alton Johnson?

15:12.056 --> 15:13.092
I did.

15:13.226 --> 15:15.096
He is a fascinating man.

15:15.230 --> 15:16.800
He's an amazing man.

15:16.933 --> 15:18.903
<i>They could rename this
town Johnsonville tomorrow,</i>

15:19.037 --> 15:20.472
and no one would complain.

15:20.607 --> 15:22.410
<i>Alton Johnson, Sr.
started the company</i>

15:22.544 --> 15:25.049
<i>in the 40s, right after
he returned from the war.</i>

15:25.182 --> 15:26.919
Back then, Brunswick
was nothing more

15:27.053 --> 15:28.623
than a spit of farmland.

15:28.757 --> 15:30.092
Was your family here then?

15:30.226 --> 15:32.263
You better believe it,
right here in this house.

15:32.397 --> 15:34.401
<i>My great-grandfather
built it himself.</i>

15:34.536 --> 15:37.340
<i>He was one of the first
people to settle here.</i>

15:37.473 --> 15:40.213
He knew Eli Brunswick,
the town's namesake.

15:40.346 --> 15:41.215
[Mary] <i>And the Johnsons?</i>

15:41.348 --> 15:42.785
[Bernice] <i>Of course.</i>

15:42.919 --> 15:44.487
<i>When Junior took over
the business in the 80s,</i>

15:44.622 --> 15:47.160
<i>the Christmas industry
was exploding.</i>

15:47.294 --> 15:49.966
But Alton, he understood
what was happening.

15:50.099 --> 15:52.237
He turned a small
family business

15:52.370 --> 15:55.009
into a multimillion-dollar
enterprise.

15:55.143 --> 15:56.378
Wow.

15:56.512 --> 15:58.550
So, it was good
timing and hard work.

15:58.683 --> 16:00.219
That's not all.

16:01.054 --> 16:02.056
Take a look.

16:02.925 --> 16:04.595
[Bernice] <i>What's it say
on the back?</i>

16:06.966 --> 16:08.035
Made in America?

16:08.168 --> 16:09.572
[Bernice] <i>Exactly.</i>

16:09.939 --> 16:11.308
When Johnson Toys
was expanding,

16:11.442 --> 16:12.978
Alton could have
shipped so much

16:13.112 --> 16:14.648
of the manufacturing overseas.

16:14.782 --> 16:17.187
<i>He could have used foreign
parts, foreign labor.</i>

16:17.320 --> 16:19.825
It would've saved him a
fortune, but he didn't.

16:19.959 --> 16:21.295
He didn't, because it also

16:21.428 --> 16:23.465
would've cost jobs
and hurt the town.

16:23.600 --> 16:25.537
That's the kind of man he is.

16:26.640 --> 16:27.507
Wow.

16:28.744 --> 16:29.778
And Blake?

16:30.647 --> 16:31.783
What about him?

16:31.917 --> 16:34.221
He's a good kid, but he
marches to his own beat.

16:34.354 --> 16:36.960
Yeah, he does seem
a little different.

16:37.093 --> 16:38.630
Different in what way?

16:39.497 --> 16:42.471
Well, certainly his father.

16:43.139 --> 16:46.111
Anyway, thanks for the insight.

16:46.245 --> 16:47.714
Happy to help.

16:49.251 --> 16:50.687
Village Tavern.

16:50.821 --> 16:51.756
Excuse me?

16:51.889 --> 16:53.292
For dinner.

16:53.425 --> 16:55.463
The Village Tavern captures
the spirit of this town,

16:55.597 --> 16:57.768
and has some darn good food.

16:58.604 --> 16:59.805
Thanks.

16:59.939 --> 17:04.213
[jazzy, festive big band music]

17:21.583 --> 17:23.720
What can I get you, ma'am?

17:23.853 --> 17:24.822
What do you recommend?

17:25.422 --> 17:28.195
For you, I'd suggest
a nice chardonnay,

17:28.329 --> 17:29.766
or maybe the Mistletoad.

17:29.899 --> 17:31.201
[Mary chuckles]

17:31.334 --> 17:32.905
I'm almost afraid to
ask, what's a Mistletoad?

17:33.038 --> 17:34.307
It's basically an Appletini,

17:34.441 --> 17:37.180
but we named it after
the Mistletoads.

17:37.815 --> 17:39.986
We're doing a special
for the 40th anniversary.

17:40.855 --> 17:43.593
Actually, I'll have what
Blake Johnson's having.

17:45.429 --> 17:46.799
You like rye, huh?

17:47.735 --> 17:48.402
Sure.

17:49.104 --> 17:55.684
Well, this brand is
distilled right here in Iowa.

17:57.053 --> 17:58.322
On the rocks.

17:59.625 --> 18:01.428
That's Mr. Johnson's drink.

18:06.238 --> 18:07.140
[Mary coughs]

18:07.273 --> 18:08.676
Yeah, that'll warm ya up.

18:10.246 --> 18:11.481
Thanks.

18:13.085 --> 18:15.056
[Lexi] <i>I feel silly
enough for thinking that.</i>

18:15.189 --> 18:16.860
[Blake] <i>No, no, no.</i>

18:16.993 --> 18:18.530
Oh, hi Mary.

18:18.664 --> 18:20.099
- Hi.
- Good to see you again.

18:20.232 --> 18:21.936
So, we're on a
first name basis now?

18:22.069 --> 18:23.372
[playful, bright music]

18:23.507 --> 18:25.043
Let me introduce you
to our VP of Marketing.

18:25.176 --> 18:26.580
Mary Romero.

18:26.713 --> 18:28.182
I'm Alexis Barnes,
I'll be with you

18:28.315 --> 18:29.652
throughout the
shoot to make sure

18:29.786 --> 18:32.389
that the messaging is on
brand for Johnson Toys.

18:32.524 --> 18:35.631
Oh, well, I'm sure
you'll be a great resource.

18:35.764 --> 18:37.668
We have an incredible
story to tell.

18:37.801 --> 18:40.640
Happy to be able to share
it with a larger audience.

18:41.308 --> 18:42.544
Me, too.

18:43.312 --> 18:46.151
Well, I was just leaving.

18:46.285 --> 18:47.521
Goodnight.

18:48.990 --> 18:50.193
Mary, I'll see you tomorrow.

18:50.326 --> 18:51.562
Great.

18:54.234 --> 18:56.271
Alton didn't mention her to me.

18:56.405 --> 18:57.541
Sounds about right.

18:57.674 --> 18:59.111
Dad's got a bit of
a one-track mind.

18:59.244 --> 19:00.814
[Mary chuckles]

19:02.551 --> 19:06.224
Um, did you want
to stay, join me?

19:07.861 --> 19:09.497
Yeah, sure.

19:10.266 --> 19:11.134
Thanks.

19:11.268 --> 19:12.370
[Mary giggles]

19:18.348 --> 19:19.618
[ice clinks]

19:19.752 --> 19:20.988
Rye?

19:21.121 --> 19:22.424
You know, this
particular brand

19:22.558 --> 19:25.195
was actually distilled
right here in Iowa.

19:26.833 --> 19:28.001
Yeah.

19:28.135 --> 19:29.170
To keeping things local.

19:29.304 --> 19:30.807
- Here, here.
- [glasses clink]

19:31.709 --> 19:34.848
[Roberta] <i>And one
special for you.</i>

19:34.982 --> 19:36.886
<i>Let me know if I can
get you anything else.</i>

19:37.020 --> 19:37.921
Thank you, Roberta.

19:38.055 --> 19:39.023
[Roberta] <i>You got it.</i>

19:39.157 --> 19:40.426
So, your father, he also likes

19:40.560 --> 19:41.829
to keep things
local, doesn't he?

19:41.962 --> 19:43.800
You just can't help
yourself, can you?

19:43.933 --> 19:47.607
I'm here for the story,
not just for the, meatloaf?

19:48.141 --> 19:51.583
Oh, no, no, no, this
is not just any meatloaf.

19:51.716 --> 19:54.120
This is the best meatloaf
west of the Mississippi.

19:54.254 --> 19:55.322
Really?

19:55.456 --> 19:56.391
- Yeah.
- That is a bold claim.

19:56.525 --> 19:57.928
It's a fact.

19:58.362 --> 20:00.466
Okay, I'll make you a deal.

20:00.868 --> 20:05.209
I will order that meatloaf, if
you'll answer some questions.

20:05.610 --> 20:07.346
You drive a hard bargain.

20:07.480 --> 20:09.283
All right, got yourself a deal.

20:09.718 --> 20:10.620
Great.

20:14.628 --> 20:15.964
Do you really like rye?

20:16.098 --> 20:17.133
I do not like it.

20:17.668 --> 20:20.940
[soft, bright music]

20:26.953 --> 20:27.921
So?

20:29.825 --> 20:30.894
All right.

20:31.028 --> 20:31.796
I concede.

20:31.929 --> 20:32.731
[Blake chuckles]

20:32.865 --> 20:34.201
[Mary] <i>You win, it's amazing.</i>

20:34.836 --> 20:36.573
Now, you have to
answer some questions.

20:36.706 --> 20:38.175
Yeah, a deal's a deal.

20:38.308 --> 20:39.779
- [Mary] <i>Okay. Okay.</i>
- Fire away.

20:40.313 --> 20:41.582
Have you lived
here all your life?

20:41.716 --> 20:42.918
[Blake] <i>Born and bred.</i>

20:43.051 --> 20:44.121
Would you leave?

20:44.254 --> 20:45.389
Nope.

20:45.524 --> 20:46.992
[Mary] <i>So, you like it?</i>

20:47.126 --> 20:48.129
It's home.

20:48.262 --> 20:49.430
That's not really an answer.

20:49.565 --> 20:51.635
And that really
wasn't a question.

20:55.511 --> 20:56.946
Don't you ever get--

20:57.079 --> 20:58.182
[Blake] <i>What?</i>

20:58.315 --> 20:59.450
Bored?

21:02.089 --> 21:02.958
Never.

21:04.060 --> 21:05.797
[mellow rock music]

21:05.931 --> 21:10.607
♪<i>♪ Come one, come all,
let's deck the halls ♪</i>

21:10.740 --> 21:16.317
♪<i>♪ The time is here to
spread some cheer ♪</i>

21:16.451 --> 21:22.163
♪<i>♪ Eggnog and pies and
twinkling lights ♪</i>

21:22.297 --> 21:24.969
♪<i>♪ are just some signs ♪</i>

21:25.102 --> 21:26.572
So, what does Mary Romero do

21:26.706 --> 21:29.043
when she's not speaking
truth to power?

21:30.112 --> 21:32.183
Well, it's not a 9-to-5 job.

21:32.317 --> 21:34.087
I go where the story is.

21:34.220 --> 21:35.322
Sounds exciting.

21:35.456 --> 21:36.391
It can be.

21:36.526 --> 21:38.028
Well, it used to be.

21:38.161 --> 21:40.800
You know, I didn't always
wanna be a reporter.

21:40.934 --> 21:41.936
Really?

21:42.070 --> 21:43.339
No.

21:43.472 --> 21:46.278
Growing up, I wanted
to get into politics,

21:46.411 --> 21:47.715
to make a difference.

21:47.848 --> 21:50.019
I mean, I was captain
of the debate team,

21:50.153 --> 21:53.492
I was class president, I even
majored in political science.

21:53.893 --> 21:56.665
And then, I got a job at
my college's news station,

21:56.799 --> 21:59.437
and it just kind of
took off from there.

21:59.572 --> 22:02.010
It seemed like another
way to help people, but--

22:02.143 --> 22:03.312
It does though, right?

22:03.846 --> 22:05.416
[Mary] <i>I don't know.</i>

22:05.550 --> 22:07.921
You know, sometimes, it just
feels like nobody's listening.

22:08.623 --> 22:11.629
But okay, enough about
me, I'm not the story.

22:11.763 --> 22:13.733
Okay, what would you
like to talk about.

22:13.866 --> 22:16.672
Alton Sr. and how he
started the business.

22:16.805 --> 22:20.714
Well, we come from
a family of farmers.

22:20.848 --> 22:24.387
But my grandpa, he was
always a talented artist.

22:24.522 --> 22:25.991
I mean, even as a little kid.

22:26.124 --> 22:28.964
<i>And then, after the war,
he started painting.</i>

22:29.097 --> 22:30.399
Professionally?

22:30.533 --> 22:32.003
<i>Yeah, it was a hobby
at first, but</i>

22:32.136 --> 22:33.673
then people started buying
those Christmas paintings,

22:33.807 --> 22:36.311
like the one that you
saw, as holiday gifts.

22:36.780 --> 22:39.317
[Mary] <i>Wow, so he did well.</i>

22:39.450 --> 22:40.954
As well as could be expected

22:41.088 --> 22:43.458
in a small town in
the middle of nowhere.

22:43.593 --> 22:46.331
So, how did he go
from Christmas paintings

22:46.464 --> 22:48.035
to a toy empire?

22:48.169 --> 22:50.205
My dad, he was born
right before Christmas.

22:50.907 --> 22:53.412
My grandparents, they didn't
have a lot of money back then.

22:53.546 --> 22:55.349
My grandpa, he couldn't
bear the thought

22:55.482 --> 22:57.019
<i>of not having a
gift for his son.</i>

22:57.153 --> 23:01.361
So, that Christmas, he made
the very first Johnson toy,

23:01.494 --> 23:03.132
and he gave it to
his newborn son.

23:03.265 --> 23:05.971
Well, Alton Sr. sounds
like an amazing man.

23:06.104 --> 23:07.439
Ah, you have no idea.

23:07.974 --> 23:10.345
And with the labor market
and the advancements

23:10.479 --> 23:14.320
<i>in manufacturing after the
war, he saw his opportunity.</i>

23:14.888 --> 23:17.695
10 years later, that
little company was

23:17.828 --> 23:19.297
well on its way to
becoming one of the top

23:19.430 --> 23:21.034
toy manufacturers
in the country.

23:21.168 --> 23:22.470
Wow.

23:22.604 --> 23:24.140
So, what happened when
your dad took over?

23:24.273 --> 23:26.278
Oh, that's when it
went into overdrive.

23:26.411 --> 23:27.848
[Mary chuckles]

23:27.981 --> 23:29.551
So, that's when
the company expanded,

23:29.685 --> 23:31.889
and you started selling
Christmas decorations.

23:32.023 --> 23:35.329
Yep. Tinsel, toys,
stockings, ornaments.

23:35.462 --> 23:38.402
Whatever he could make and
whatever people would buy.

23:38.536 --> 23:40.005
So, no more painting?

23:40.540 --> 23:41.843
No.

23:41.976 --> 23:43.646
Grandpa had to give
that up as a business,

23:43.779 --> 23:46.785
but I mean, he still
painted until his dying day.

23:47.521 --> 23:48.723
He loved it.

23:49.558 --> 23:50.793
Come on.

23:54.200 --> 23:57.206
[bright, acoustic music]

24:01.314 --> 24:02.550
[Blake] <i>Okay.</i>

24:03.251 --> 24:04.320
Here we are.

24:04.855 --> 24:06.291
Is this your house?

24:06.759 --> 24:09.330
No, I live right off
town square in a home

24:09.464 --> 24:11.200
that's probably too big for me.

24:11.735 --> 24:13.940
Okay, so what is this place?

24:14.073 --> 24:16.679
This is my
grandpa's first house.

24:16.812 --> 24:18.215
He built it with
his own two hands.

24:18.349 --> 24:19.652
[Mary] <i>Wow.</i>

24:19.785 --> 24:20.954
[Blake] <i>He was quite
the craftsman.</i>

24:21.088 --> 24:22.290
Yeah, I bet it
was really beautiful

24:22.423 --> 24:25.664
when it was, you know, new.

24:25.797 --> 24:26.866
[Blake] <i>Yeah.</i>

24:26.999 --> 24:28.769
Once my dad took
over the company,

24:28.903 --> 24:30.506
he moved my grandparents
into a much nicer house,

24:30.640 --> 24:33.144
and he left this to
just sit here empty.

24:33.813 --> 24:36.919
My dad's very generous,
just hardly sentimental.

24:37.052 --> 24:38.556
Well, someone should
have stepped in,

24:38.690 --> 24:40.192
because there's a
lot of history here.

24:40.325 --> 24:41.629
Someone did.

24:41.762 --> 24:43.566
[Blake chuckles]
I'm restoring it.

24:44.434 --> 24:46.973
I'm gonna turn it into a gallery
for my grandpa's paintings.

24:47.106 --> 24:48.776
Oh, I love that.

24:48.909 --> 24:50.312
I already restored
a vintage tractor

24:50.446 --> 24:52.116
I found just sitting here.

24:52.784 --> 24:54.655
Now, it's just sitting
in my front yard.

24:54.789 --> 24:56.190
[Mary giggles]

24:57.360 --> 24:58.596
Wow.

25:03.271 --> 25:04.508
[phone camera clicks]

25:05.176 --> 25:06.111
What are you doing?

25:06.244 --> 25:07.781
I'm just gonna
take a few photos,

25:07.915 --> 25:09.217
and then I can send the
cameraman over here,

25:09.351 --> 25:10.653
and he can shoot it properly.

25:10.787 --> 25:13.124
No, no, I'd prefer
if you didn't do that.

25:14.628 --> 25:15.997
Why are you showing me this

25:16.131 --> 25:17.433
if you don't want it to
be part of the story?

25:18.101 --> 25:19.705
Thought you'd appreciate it.

25:20.172 --> 25:21.008
Was I wrong?

25:21.141 --> 25:22.109
[Mary chuckles]

25:24.214 --> 25:26.652
No, no, not really.

25:28.589 --> 25:29.625
Okay.

25:30.192 --> 25:31.796
It would really help
the story, though.

25:31.929 --> 25:33.265
Yeah, something tells me,

25:33.399 --> 25:34.768
you know how to get a
story without this in it.

25:37.206 --> 25:37.874
[Mary sighs]

25:38.007 --> 25:41.281
[mellow, soulful music]

25:41.414 --> 25:45.122
♪<i>♪ We don't see each
other nearly enough ♪</i>

25:45.255 --> 25:49.464
♪<i>♪ But I love every
moment with you ♪</i>

25:49.598 --> 25:52.504
♪<i>♪ I was thinking 'bout
the last time we talked ♪</i>

25:52.637 --> 25:57.446
♪<i>♪ And had a good laugh
with a good glass or two ♪</i>

25:57.581 --> 26:01.989
♪<i>♪ But who's counting, not
me when I'm with you, baby ♪</i>

26:02.122 --> 26:05.496
♪<i>♪ No doubting, the
vibe that you give me ♪</i>

26:05.630 --> 26:12.109
♪<i>♪ Ooh, you're the reason this
season's so pleasing to me ♪</i>

26:12.242 --> 26:15.482
♪<i>♪ There's nowhere
I'd rather be ♪</i>

26:15.617 --> 26:17.119
[Mary grunts]

26:18.422 --> 26:23.666
♪<i>♪ With you I'm moving, I'm
grooving, so soothing, yeah ♪</i>

26:23.799 --> 26:26.304
♪<i>♪ If you feel the way I do ♪</i>

26:26.437 --> 26:29.645
♪<i>♪ We don't have to
wait to celebrate ♪</i>

26:29.778 --> 26:32.049
♪<i>♪ Don't wait to celebrate ♪</i>

26:32.183 --> 26:33.853
[phone rings]

26:35.356 --> 26:36.190
Oh.

26:36.324 --> 26:36.992
Hey, Bree.

26:37.125 --> 26:38.361
[Brianna] <i>Hey, girl.</i>

26:38.495 --> 26:40.065
Just got back from dinner.

26:40.198 --> 26:42.269
Oh, with Crunch?

26:42.402 --> 26:43.506
What's his name, Crank?

26:43.639 --> 26:44.374
[Mary chuckles]

26:44.508 --> 26:45.743
With Crash.

26:45.876 --> 26:47.112
No, he doesn't get
here until tomorrow.

26:48.182 --> 26:49.217
So, what's up?

26:49.450 --> 26:50.419
[Bree] <i>Nothing.</i>

26:50.553 --> 26:52.290
I just needed a break.

26:52.423 --> 26:53.860
Dylan's working late.

26:53.993 --> 26:55.196
[Mary] <i>Oh, okay.</i>

26:55.329 --> 26:56.798
I'm so glad I could
be your backup.

26:56.932 --> 26:58.268
[Bree] <i>Yeah,
everything's cool here.</i>

26:58.402 --> 26:59.938
I mean, the main
construction guy stopped by.

27:00.071 --> 27:02.811
He said he's on schedule
to start tomorrow.

27:03.412 --> 27:04.548
How's nowheresville?

27:04.682 --> 27:06.652
You mean Brunswick?

27:07.253 --> 27:08.455
[Mary] <i>It's fine.</i>

27:08.589 --> 27:11.427
[Brianna] <i>Any cute
toymakers, or farmers?</i>

27:12.798 --> 27:14.167
There might be.

27:14.300 --> 27:15.069
[Bree] <i>What?</i>

27:15.202 --> 27:17.808
Oh my God, tell me, tell me.

27:18.208 --> 27:21.280
I mean, if you're into
hot guys from the country.

27:21.414 --> 27:22.717
Oh, I'm totally into you

27:22.851 --> 27:24.622
being into hot guys
from the country.

27:24.755 --> 27:25.723
So, are you?

27:25.857 --> 27:26.926
[Mary laughs]

27:27.426 --> 27:29.965
I don't know, it's
too soon to tell.

27:30.098 --> 27:32.003
It is never too early
for love at first sight.

27:32.136 --> 27:34.975
<i>What is he, is he a
toymaker, a farmer?</i>

27:35.109 --> 27:36.712
<i>I know there are farmers.</i>

27:36.845 --> 27:38.148
He's a toymaker.

27:38.282 --> 27:39.283
Ah, yes.

27:39.417 --> 27:40.686
And he runs the factory.

27:40.820 --> 27:43.491
Well, his family
owns the company, so.

27:43.626 --> 27:45.596
O-M-G, I love this.

27:45.730 --> 27:47.033
[Brianna giggles]

27:47.166 --> 27:48.535
I'll have to tell you
everything tomorrow,

27:48.669 --> 27:50.105
'cause I have so
much work to do.

27:50.239 --> 27:51.474
Living the dream.

27:51.608 --> 27:52.744
I demand a full report.

27:52.877 --> 27:54.347
I'm so bored,
I need some drama.

27:54.480 --> 27:57.987
Okay, well I report the
drama, I don't make it, so.

27:58.121 --> 27:59.825
I respect that, I see you.

27:59.958 --> 28:01.461
Okay, well call me tomorrow.

28:01.595 --> 28:05.202
Sweet dreams, of your
Christmas toymaker.

28:05.336 --> 28:06.103
[Mary giggles]

28:06.237 --> 28:07.472
Okay, bye.

28:11.615 --> 28:15.790
[upbeat, bright, festive music]

28:26.679 --> 28:28.749
[door knocks]

28:31.454 --> 28:32.724
[Mary sighs]

28:39.571 --> 28:41.207
What took you so long?

28:41.340 --> 28:42.810
I've been knocking
for five minutes.

28:42.944 --> 28:44.480
I wasn't just
sitting by the door,

28:44.614 --> 28:45.850
waiting for you to get here.

28:46.250 --> 28:49.190
You didn't have to get all
dressed up on account of me.

28:50.092 --> 28:52.430
I was up all night, just
going through all of that.

28:52.964 --> 28:55.001
[Crash] <i>An
embarrassment of riches.</i>

28:55.435 --> 28:56.539
Have fun.

28:56.672 --> 28:58.441
Yeah, well that is gonna
make your job easier.

28:58.576 --> 29:00.880
The more material they give
us, the less you have to shoot.

29:01.014 --> 29:03.185
I'll tell you what
would make my job easier.

29:03.318 --> 29:06.324
A sound mixer and a
production assistant.

29:06.458 --> 29:07.660
I'm getting too
old to be dragging

29:07.794 --> 29:09.330
all my gear from here to there.

29:09.463 --> 29:12.436
Yeah, well, welcome to
the new millennium, Crash.

29:12.571 --> 29:13.706
[Crash sighs]

29:13.839 --> 29:15.142
Just go downstairs
and check in.

29:15.275 --> 29:17.079
I'm gonna take a shower,
I'll meet you down there,

29:17.213 --> 29:19.383
we can get a bite to eat, okay?

29:19.518 --> 29:20.787
- Okay.
- Okay.

29:20.920 --> 29:23.258
But hurry up, I'm starving.

29:23.391 --> 29:24.293
Okay.

29:29.804 --> 29:30.973
[Mary sighs]

29:31.575 --> 29:32.442
Okay.

29:38.823 --> 29:40.492
Hello, dear. How'd you sleep?

29:40.627 --> 29:41.862
Good morning.

29:41.995 --> 29:44.000
I slept fine, 'til
this one woke me up.

29:44.133 --> 29:47.439
She thinks she's on vacation,
sleeping the day away.

29:47.573 --> 29:49.410
I thought that we
were gonna go get food.

29:49.544 --> 29:50.913
Oh, it's my fault.

29:51.047 --> 29:53.484
When he mentioned he was
hungry, I couldn't resist.

29:54.320 --> 29:54.989
Uh-huh.

29:55.122 --> 29:56.391
You won't some?

29:56.525 --> 29:59.296
No, thank you, I'll pass.

29:59.430 --> 30:02.136
The trick is to salt the
eggs before you scramble them.

30:02.269 --> 30:03.773
<i>Makes 'em creamier.</i>

30:03.906 --> 30:05.510
Thanks for the
tip, do you wanna?

30:05.644 --> 30:06.946
You go.

30:07.079 --> 30:10.419
She's making cinnamon
rolls, from scratch.

30:10.553 --> 30:12.089
<i>I'll meet you later.</i>

30:12.489 --> 30:15.429
- Okay, we have work to do.
- [Crash] <i>Mm-hmm.</i>

30:15.564 --> 30:17.099
[Bernice] <i>Don't worry,
I'll make sure</i>

30:17.232 --> 30:19.236
and point him in
the right direction.

30:19.738 --> 30:21.040
Thank you.

30:21.174 --> 30:23.078
[mellow rock music]

30:23.211 --> 30:26.786
♪<i>♪ A Merry Christmas ♪</i>

30:26.919 --> 30:32.095
♪<i>♪ Merry Christmas to all ♪</i>

30:36.070 --> 30:39.678
♪<i>♪ So, let the snowballs fly
and the good times roll ♪</i>

30:39.811 --> 30:43.552
♪<i>♪ Before your Great Aunt
Sadie finds the mistletoe ♪</i>

30:45.488 --> 30:47.593
[Blake groans]
Awful, isn't it?

30:48.596 --> 30:50.031
Your words, not mine.

30:50.900 --> 30:52.136
How'd you sleep?

30:52.370 --> 30:54.508
Why does everyone in this
town keep asking me that?

30:54.641 --> 30:56.579
I guess because when
people come to visit,

30:56.712 --> 30:58.949
they always say it's the
best sleep they ever had.

30:59.083 --> 31:00.653
No, no, not for me.

31:00.786 --> 31:04.561
I miss the sirens and the
honking and the yelling.

31:04.695 --> 31:06.197
You know, the city.

31:06.331 --> 31:08.034
- [Mary giggles]
- Hmm.

31:08.167 --> 31:09.336
Anyway, I was up really late

31:09.470 --> 31:11.174
prepping for your
dad's interview, so.

31:11.307 --> 31:12.911
No, you don't have
to worry about that.

31:13.044 --> 31:14.079
There's no one who
likes to talk more

31:14.213 --> 31:16.518
about the company, or himself.

31:16.852 --> 31:19.724
Well, maybe someone is
actually embracing this story.

31:19.858 --> 31:21.294
Wow, if I didn't
know any better,

31:21.428 --> 31:23.899
I'd say, you're trying to
guilt me into participating.

31:24.467 --> 31:25.402
Would it work?

31:25.536 --> 31:26.672
What do you think?

31:26.806 --> 31:28.910
I think I need a really
good cup of coffee.

31:29.043 --> 31:30.378
Any suggestions?

31:30.513 --> 31:31.716
I happen to know
who makes the meanest

31:31.849 --> 31:33.853
peppermint latte in town.

31:33.986 --> 31:35.355
[Mary chuckles]

31:35.489 --> 31:37.192
I'm sorry, you just don't
normally hear "meanest"

31:37.326 --> 31:38.896
and "peppermint latte"
in the same sentence.

31:39.029 --> 31:41.500
Well, clearly you've never
had this peppermint latte.

31:41.635 --> 31:44.674
[soft, bright music]

31:55.495 --> 31:57.601
You know, I am usually a
black coffee kind of girl,

31:57.734 --> 32:01.274
but as far as peppermint
lattes go, it's pretty mean.

32:01.408 --> 32:03.078
Well, that makes
me two-for-two.

32:03.211 --> 32:04.714
You should be a tour guide.

32:04.848 --> 32:06.551
Can't escape the holiday
spirit in this town.

32:06.685 --> 32:08.556
No, you can't.

32:08.689 --> 32:10.058
Is that why you stay?

32:10.192 --> 32:11.360
Excuse me?

32:11.494 --> 32:12.898
In Brunswick, at
your family's company?

32:13.031 --> 32:14.433
You could go somewhere else,

32:14.567 --> 32:16.672
you could do
whatever you wanted.

32:16.806 --> 32:19.711
I mean, do you really like
working at the company?

32:19.845 --> 32:22.149
I may not agree with
all my dad's decisions,

32:22.283 --> 32:24.387
but hundreds of workers depend

32:24.521 --> 32:26.223
on our company for
their livelihood.

32:26.357 --> 32:28.962
That's just a responsibility
I don't take lightly.

32:29.096 --> 32:30.566
Wow.

32:30.699 --> 32:32.069
That's refreshing.

32:32.202 --> 32:33.505
[Blake] <i>What is?</i>

32:33.639 --> 32:36.711
Staying at a job for
altruistic reasons.

32:36.845 --> 32:38.849
Oh, I think you've
been covering politics

32:38.982 --> 32:40.019
a little too long.

32:40.152 --> 32:41.021
[Mary chuckles]

32:41.154 --> 32:42.557
Well, probably.

32:44.193 --> 32:46.699
<i>So, that's the only
reason you stay,</i>

32:46.832 --> 32:49.069
just out of responsibility?

32:49.972 --> 32:51.307
[Blake] <i>Nah, you'll laugh.</i>

32:51.440 --> 32:52.911
Believe it or not,
but I have never

32:53.044 --> 32:54.647
been accused of
laughing too easily.

32:54.781 --> 32:56.317
[Blake chuckles]
Right.

32:59.123 --> 33:00.325
I like Christmas.

33:00.458 --> 33:02.196
You what?
[Mary giggles]

33:02.329 --> 33:03.866
You said you wouldn't laugh.

33:03.999 --> 33:05.937
No, I'm not laughing
because of that.

33:06.070 --> 33:07.373
It's just, after everything

33:07.507 --> 33:09.043
that you've said
about Mistletoads.

33:09.176 --> 33:11.014
Yeah, well look, I
may not be enamored

33:11.147 --> 33:12.784
with all the things
we manufacture,

33:12.917 --> 33:16.323
but it doesn't mean that I
don't understand their purpose.

33:16.457 --> 33:19.262
We're a big part of people's
Christmas traditions.

33:19.964 --> 33:23.572
You know, it is a shame that
I can't put that in my piece.

33:24.741 --> 33:27.212
So, am I gonna see you
later this afternoon

33:27.345 --> 33:28.816
when I interview Alton?

33:28.949 --> 33:29.817
This time of year?

33:29.951 --> 33:31.254
No, sorry.

33:31.387 --> 33:33.926
We're way too busy
for me to step away.

33:34.060 --> 33:35.328
Maybe you'll change your mind.

33:35.461 --> 33:37.032
Someone's gotta run
the factory, Mary.

33:37.165 --> 33:39.671
Santa and those elves, they
can't do it all by themselves.

33:39.804 --> 33:40.973
They can't.

33:41.107 --> 33:42.209
Would you go on the
record with that?

33:42.343 --> 33:43.277
Because that is a scoop.

33:43.411 --> 33:44.781
You are relentless.

33:44.915 --> 33:46.150
You have no idea.

33:46.652 --> 33:49.189
I'm starting to
get a sense of it.

33:50.960 --> 33:51.962
I gotta go.

33:52.597 --> 33:54.634
I have a one-man crew,
and as awesome as he is,

33:54.768 --> 33:57.339
it's gonna take a
while to set up, so.

34:00.278 --> 34:01.314
Guess I'll see you around?

34:01.447 --> 34:02.650
[Mary] <i>See ya.</i>

34:02.784 --> 34:06.056
[soft, tender music]

34:12.403 --> 34:15.341
Hey, you missed Bernice's
savory cinnamon rolls.

34:15.475 --> 34:17.179
Just like my mama used to make.

34:17.312 --> 34:19.483
Crash, can we talk
about that later?

34:19.617 --> 34:21.186
Did you do this?

34:21.320 --> 34:22.757
[Crash] <i>It was here
when I came in.</i>

34:22.890 --> 34:24.459
I assumed you did it.

34:24.594 --> 34:25.864
Me?

34:25.997 --> 34:27.633
<i>How many years have we
been working together?</i>

34:27.767 --> 34:31.440
Have you ever seen me stage
something this cheesy?

34:32.810 --> 34:33.679
That was me.

34:33.813 --> 34:35.015
Hey.

34:35.148 --> 34:36.685
And since the Mistletoads
are the company's

34:36.818 --> 34:39.857
most famous item, I thought
it would be appropriate.

34:39.991 --> 34:41.595
<i>I know that Alton
would like it,</i>

34:41.728 --> 34:44.266
<i>unless of course you
have a better idea?</i>

34:46.037 --> 34:47.339
You know what, it's fine.

34:50.412 --> 34:52.449
Oh, good, I see
you two have met.

34:52.583 --> 34:54.721
I asked Lexi to oversee
things on our end.

34:54.854 --> 34:57.025
Not only does she
have media experience,

34:57.158 --> 34:58.863
but she knows which
is my good side.

34:58.996 --> 35:00.398
[Alton chuckles]

35:00.532 --> 35:01.635
[Crash] <i>Come on, let's
get you mic'd up.</i>

35:02.136 --> 35:03.437
Thank you, Crash.

35:06.010 --> 35:07.780
Okay, Alton, let's get
you set up, and then,

35:07.914 --> 35:09.483
we can go ahead and go over
some of the ground rules.

35:09.617 --> 35:11.555
I am in your
very capable hands.

35:11.689 --> 35:12.790
[Mary giggles]

35:12.924 --> 35:14.694
Do I look down and
talk into that?

35:14.827 --> 35:16.731
No. You know what, just
forget that it's there.

35:16.865 --> 35:18.636
And then, when we do
start the interview,

35:18.769 --> 35:22.510
don't look in the camera,
just stay looking at me, okay?

35:23.813 --> 35:25.181
[soft, bright music]

35:25.315 --> 35:27.385
Okay, Alton, how do you feel?

35:28.387 --> 35:29.957
<i>Great, great.</i>

35:30.091 --> 35:31.360
We can see his microphone.

35:31.494 --> 35:32.997
[Mary] <i>Yeah, I'm aware.</i>

35:33.130 --> 35:34.567
<i>That's his primary mic,
though, and sound quality</i>

35:34.700 --> 35:36.571
is actually more
important than visibility.

35:36.705 --> 35:37.573
Oh.

35:39.343 --> 35:40.947
[Mary] <i>So, it's just like we
talked about earlier.</i>

35:41.080 --> 35:42.584
<i>Just look right at
me, and it's just like</i>

35:42.717 --> 35:44.019
<i>we're having a
normal conversation.</i>

35:44.153 --> 35:45.188
Camera speeds.

35:45.321 --> 35:46.792
Okay, great.

35:46.925 --> 35:48.663
So, let's go ahead and just
start at the beginning.

35:48.796 --> 35:51.702
Tell me about the
founding of Johnson Toys.

35:51.835 --> 35:53.371
In 1946--

35:53.506 --> 35:54.473
I'm so sorry, Alton.

35:54.607 --> 35:55.910
I forgot to tell you.

35:56.043 --> 35:57.680
So, you're gonna want
to rephrase the question

35:57.814 --> 35:59.818
<i>in the answer, so it'll
sound something like,</i>

35:59.951 --> 36:02.790
<i>Johnson Toys was
founded in 1946.</i>

36:02.924 --> 36:04.226
Aye aye, Captain.

36:04.359 --> 36:06.665
Stop, stop, cut.

36:07.700 --> 36:10.606
<i>That Mistletoad,
it's out of focus.</i>

36:10.739 --> 36:14.279
We can't even see what it is,
it looks like a green blob.

36:14.413 --> 36:15.816
It's supposed to
be out of focus.

36:15.949 --> 36:18.087
We want the viewers
to focus on Alton.

36:18.221 --> 36:19.390
Ah, I don't know.

36:19.524 --> 36:21.227
I think we wanna
see the Mistletoads.

36:21.361 --> 36:24.701
<i>After all, they're what we're
known for, not green blobs.</i>

36:24.834 --> 36:26.069
[Alton] <i>Yeah, I think so, too.</i>

36:26.203 --> 36:29.009
It's all about the Mistletoads.

36:29.142 --> 36:30.512
<i>What do you think, Mary?</i>

36:30.880 --> 36:34.186
How about we put it right here,
like he's my right-hand man?

36:34.320 --> 36:35.623
You know what?

36:35.756 --> 36:37.794
If it makes you happy,
Alton, that's fine.

36:37.927 --> 36:39.263
<i>Let's go again.</i>

36:39.396 --> 36:40.399
[Crash] <i>Speeding.</i>

36:40.533 --> 36:41.935
Hey, why do you say that?

36:42.068 --> 36:42.804
What?

36:42.937 --> 36:43.905
Speeding.

36:44.306 --> 36:46.110
It just confirms
that we're recording.

36:46.244 --> 36:48.849
Why not say
recording or filming?

36:48.982 --> 36:50.218
Alton, if we could just--

36:50.351 --> 36:52.156
It's a relic, really,
from the old days

36:52.289 --> 36:53.859
when you actually used film.

36:53.993 --> 36:55.996
You needed to wait a
few seconds for the film

36:56.130 --> 37:00.005
to reach the proper speed,
so you'd say "speeding."

37:00.138 --> 37:01.273
I love that.

37:01.406 --> 37:02.910
So, you just do it
out of tradition.

37:03.044 --> 37:04.246
[Crash] <i>Habit for me.</i>

37:04.379 --> 37:05.916
Tradition for the new kids.

37:06.050 --> 37:08.823
And thank you for the
history lesson, Crash.

37:08.956 --> 37:10.325
Still speeding.

37:10.458 --> 37:12.228
Shall we begin again?

37:12.362 --> 37:13.833
<i>Okay.</i>

37:13.966 --> 37:15.569
Alton, can you tell me a
little bit about the importance

37:15.703 --> 37:18.040
of Johnson Toys being
a family business?

37:18.174 --> 37:19.443
Actually--

37:19.578 --> 37:21.915
Lexi, I cannot have
all these interruptions.

37:22.049 --> 37:24.486
So, I'm gonna ask you if you
need to say something to me

37:24.621 --> 37:27.526
to wait until afterwards,
and if you can't do that,

37:27.660 --> 37:29.496
I'm gonna have to
ask you to leave.

37:34.339 --> 37:35.642
Go ahead.

37:35.776 --> 37:36.811
Thank you.

37:39.116 --> 37:41.722
You know how we came
up with the Mistletoads?

37:41.855 --> 37:44.326
Could we talk about
that in a little bit?

37:44.460 --> 37:45.529
Right now, I'd
really like to hear

37:45.663 --> 37:47.299
about how it's a
family business.

37:47.432 --> 37:50.105
Well, this is a
story about family.

37:50.773 --> 37:55.148
Blake's mother had mistletoe
up around the house.

37:55.282 --> 37:57.252
She loved Christmas.

37:57.385 --> 37:59.490
I do, too, but she
really loved it.

38:00.125 --> 38:01.995
Anyway, Blake would
smash words together

38:02.129 --> 38:03.899
when he was two or
three, and when he saw

38:04.032 --> 38:07.907
some mistletoe hanging one
day he shouted "Mistletoad!"

38:08.040 --> 38:09.343
[Alton chuckles]

38:09.476 --> 38:11.147
We just thought it was
the funniest thing.

38:11.280 --> 38:13.317
[Alton chuckles]

38:13.451 --> 38:14.988
The rest is history.

38:15.288 --> 38:19.362
<i>We drew it up that night,
and the Mistletoad was born.</i>

38:19.931 --> 38:21.267
This is great.

38:21.801 --> 38:25.441
[jazzy Christmas music]

38:26.377 --> 38:29.016
So, what do you
think, honestly?

38:29.684 --> 38:31.254
He's a natural storyteller.

38:31.387 --> 38:33.592
Plus he's funny and likable.

38:33.725 --> 38:35.028
Got nothing to worry about.

38:35.161 --> 38:36.631
Yeah, but you're not
the one that's gonna have

38:36.765 --> 38:38.201
to sift through hours
of Mistletoad talk

38:38.334 --> 38:39.437
just to find the good stuff.

38:39.571 --> 38:40.940
Well, that's the job.

38:41.575 --> 38:42.475
Yeah, but what about Lexi?

38:42.610 --> 38:43.879
Can you believe her?

38:44.013 --> 38:46.116
You've dealt with plenty
of PR flacks before,

38:46.249 --> 38:47.352
who were just as pushy.

38:47.485 --> 38:48.655
Yeah.

38:48.789 --> 38:50.391
The politics on this
one, it's tricky.

38:50.526 --> 38:53.431
I mean, how are we supposed to
maintain integrity like this?

38:53.565 --> 38:54.935
You just stick to your guns.

38:55.068 --> 38:56.871
Now, we've worked
together a long time,

38:57.005 --> 38:59.510
and there's one thing I've come
to learn about Mary Romero,

38:59.644 --> 39:04.252
is that she brings integrity
into everything she does.

39:04.386 --> 39:05.288
You got this.

39:05.421 --> 39:07.927
Crash, you old softie.

39:08.061 --> 39:10.465
Well, I just call
it like I see it.

39:10.599 --> 39:12.202
Well, thank you.

39:13.070 --> 39:16.511
Oh, you wanna screen some
footage with me tonight?

39:17.145 --> 39:18.548
No can do.

39:18.682 --> 39:19.551
I have plans.

39:19.684 --> 39:20.820
You have plans?

39:20.953 --> 39:22.289
- Mmm.
- Here, in Brunswick, Iowa.

39:22.423 --> 39:23.291
Please.

39:23.424 --> 39:24.994
I make friends easily.

39:25.128 --> 39:27.566
You are the biggest
misanthrope I know.

39:27.700 --> 39:29.402
[both chuckle]

39:30.438 --> 39:31.173
[soft, bright music]

39:31.306 --> 39:32.475
What?

39:32.610 --> 39:34.514
Bernice offered
to cook me dinner.

39:34.647 --> 39:36.450
We got to talking
about mushrooms.

39:36.585 --> 39:38.822
Years ago, I did a piece
on truffle hunters,

39:38.956 --> 39:43.264
and it turns out she
forages her own mushrooms.

39:43.398 --> 39:45.068
What is going on?

39:45.201 --> 39:47.507
You have a date, and
I have a PR person

39:47.640 --> 39:49.577
telling me how to
direct my shoot.

39:49.711 --> 39:51.079
Is this the Twilight Zone?

39:51.213 --> 39:55.822
Nope, just Christmas
time, season for miracles.

39:57.459 --> 39:58.962
And speaking of miracles.

39:59.096 --> 39:59.964
Thank you.

40:01.668 --> 40:02.870
Thank you.

40:04.974 --> 40:05.842
Mmm.

40:07.079 --> 40:07.947
A date.

40:10.085 --> 40:11.153
Mmm, fries are good.

40:11.287 --> 40:12.155
Try 'em.

40:15.228 --> 40:17.131
- Mm-hmm.
- Mm-hmm.

40:17.265 --> 40:20.071
[mellow rock music]

40:53.071 --> 40:54.607
[door knocks]

41:06.765 --> 41:08.267
[door knocks]

41:21.026 --> 41:21.928
Hey.

41:23.064 --> 41:24.199
No solicitors.

41:24.734 --> 41:25.836
What are you doing?

41:25.970 --> 41:27.739
Oh, I was taking a shower.

41:27.873 --> 41:29.410
One second, I'll be right down.

41:29.544 --> 41:30.779
Okay.

41:47.680 --> 41:49.617
- Hi.
- Hi.

41:51.654 --> 41:53.057
How'd you know where I live?

41:54.426 --> 41:55.595
Right off the town square,

41:55.729 --> 41:57.298
vintage tractor
in the front yard.

41:57.432 --> 41:59.504
I mean, even in a farming
town, that's not really

41:59.637 --> 42:02.308
a dime a dozen, so
it wasn't that hard.

42:03.845 --> 42:05.048
Come inside, it's freezing.

42:05.181 --> 42:06.249
Yeah, okay.

42:09.456 --> 42:10.892
[Mary giggles]

42:11.026 --> 42:13.330
You always have a fire
burning for all your guests?

42:13.464 --> 42:15.301
I was just about to
settle in, do some work.

42:15.435 --> 42:16.838
Oh yeah?

42:16.971 --> 42:18.140
What can I do for you,
Mary, besides warm you up?

42:19.644 --> 42:22.048
I mean, with the fire.

42:22.181 --> 42:23.317
I know that.

42:24.955 --> 42:28.060
So, how did the interview go?

42:29.229 --> 42:32.168
I mean, don't
you already know?

42:32.302 --> 42:33.672
What do you mean?

42:33.805 --> 42:36.076
You had Lexi
there to spy on me.

42:36.210 --> 42:39.650
No, Lexi does not wait on
my instructions on anything.

42:39.784 --> 42:43.223
Right, but you guys
are, you know, like.

42:43.959 --> 42:45.328
What are you doing?

42:45.863 --> 42:47.833
I'm trying to say that
you're together, right?

42:48.768 --> 42:50.572
Lexi grew up
here, and so did I.

42:50.706 --> 42:52.777
We went to the same
schools together.

42:52.910 --> 42:54.848
Let's just say there
weren't a lot of options,

42:54.981 --> 42:57.218
you know, for either of us.

42:57.352 --> 42:58.288
So, you dated.

42:58.421 --> 42:59.891
A lifetime ago.

43:00.024 --> 43:02.396
Yeah, and now she works
for you, which is not weird.

43:02.530 --> 43:03.799
It's not weird for me.

43:03.932 --> 43:05.368
I don't think it's
weird for her.

43:05.502 --> 43:06.871
Is it weird for you?

43:07.005 --> 43:08.708
Why would it be weird for me?

43:11.080 --> 43:14.486
Is that why you came
by, to chat about Lexi?

43:14.620 --> 43:16.323
No, you distracted me.

43:16.456 --> 43:18.862
Oh, I'm sorry, I think.

43:19.864 --> 43:23.672
Look, I came by to ask
you to please reconsider.

43:23.805 --> 43:25.441
Oh, you really
don't give up, do you?

43:25.575 --> 43:27.680
Blake, this story
is gonna happen,

43:27.814 --> 43:29.717
whether you want it to or not.

43:29.851 --> 43:32.623
Don't you want your story
to be told correctly?

43:32.757 --> 43:34.359
That's what Lexi keeps saying.

43:34.492 --> 43:37.231
You know, get in front of
it, control the narrative.

43:37.365 --> 43:38.468
Exactly.

43:38.602 --> 43:41.173
Lexi and I agree,
just this once.

43:42.542 --> 43:44.412
You know what? Come on.

43:45.916 --> 43:47.385
[Mary sighs]

43:48.588 --> 43:50.659
[fire crackles]

43:51.460 --> 43:54.634
[soft, bright music]

43:54.767 --> 43:56.002
[Mary] Wow.

43:56.738 --> 43:57.573
Are these?

43:57.707 --> 43:59.309
My grandpa's, yeah.

44:02.482 --> 44:03.484
[Mary] <i>Really?</i>

44:04.019 --> 44:07.225
Some of them just look a
little more contemporary.

44:07.358 --> 44:09.998
You know, he was
ahead of his time.

44:10.131 --> 44:11.166
Sure.

44:13.170 --> 44:14.206
Wow.

44:14.774 --> 44:16.744
You know, Brunswick
is a lot more

44:16.877 --> 44:18.314
than just Johnson Toys.

44:18.882 --> 44:20.251
I do know that, yeah.

44:20.384 --> 44:22.355
Unfortunately,
not everyone does.

44:23.057 --> 44:24.928
This town is hurting.

44:25.061 --> 44:27.265
Well, they just need to
look at your annual budget.

44:27.399 --> 44:28.969
I mean, you're receiving
less and less money

44:29.102 --> 44:30.405
from the state each year.

44:30.539 --> 44:32.041
You're cutting back on
the schools, the clinic.

44:32.442 --> 44:33.712
I do my homework.

44:34.246 --> 44:37.152
Well then, you also know
that we're having a hard time

44:37.285 --> 44:39.690
filling the empty
seats on town council.

44:40.959 --> 44:42.763
Nobody wants to face the music.

44:42.897 --> 44:44.499
That's what I'm talking about.

44:44.633 --> 44:45.969
This piece could bring Brunswick

44:46.103 --> 44:48.775
exactly the type of
exposure that you need.

44:50.277 --> 44:51.548
It could.

44:51.681 --> 44:55.154
[bright, playful music]

44:57.492 --> 45:00.030
If I did this,

45:01.032 --> 45:02.703
I'd be trusting you to tell

45:02.836 --> 45:04.574
the real story
about the company.

45:05.274 --> 45:08.648
How Johnson Toys is more
than just Mistletoads.

45:08.782 --> 45:10.151
What we mean to this town,

45:10.284 --> 45:12.489
and what this town
means to my family.

45:13.057 --> 45:15.729
Something that my grandpa
would be proud of.

45:17.232 --> 45:19.202
I wouldn't have
it any other way.

45:24.814 --> 45:26.049
What?

45:26.818 --> 45:28.453
Told you I'd get
you to say yes.

45:33.497 --> 45:34.265
It's my turn.

45:34.399 --> 45:35.535
No, it's not.

45:35.669 --> 45:36.737
It's mine.

45:36.871 --> 45:37.706
It's my turn.
There you go.

45:37.839 --> 45:39.309
[Bernice] <i>You're so bad.</i>

45:45.689 --> 45:46.958
Candy cane.

45:49.597 --> 45:51.499
[Crash] <i>What are you
so happy about?</i>

45:52.670 --> 45:54.205
Blake agreed to my interview.

45:54.807 --> 45:56.109
- Really?
- [Mary] <i>Mm-hmm.</i>

45:56.242 --> 45:58.013
I thought he was
dead set against it.

45:58.147 --> 46:01.821
He was, but I feel like
we're really connecting.

46:01.954 --> 46:03.190
I bet.

46:04.492 --> 46:05.895
How was dinner?

46:06.496 --> 46:07.800
Hmm, so-so.

46:07.933 --> 46:08.801
[Mary gasps]

46:08.935 --> 46:10.539
He had two helpings.

46:10.673 --> 46:12.777
He would've had more, but I
made him save room for dessert.

46:12.910 --> 46:15.582
I was hungry after
a hard day's work.

46:15.715 --> 46:16.851
That's all.

46:16.984 --> 46:18.955
Had nothing to do with the meal.

46:19.089 --> 46:20.559
- [leg thuds]
- [Crash groans]

46:20.692 --> 46:22.763
You guys, you are too much.

46:22.896 --> 46:24.432
What about you, dear?

46:24.567 --> 46:25.936
Can I fix you something?

46:26.069 --> 46:28.509
No, thank you, I have
a lot of work to do.

46:28.642 --> 46:29.710
[tongue clicks]

46:29.844 --> 46:31.046
Goodnight.

46:31.781 --> 46:35.522
[festive, bright rock music]

46:35.655 --> 46:39.496
♪<i>♪ Aw, yeah ♪</i>

46:39.630 --> 46:44.006
♪<i>♪ Mm-hmm ♪</i>

46:44.139 --> 46:49.516
♪<i>♪ It's time when we're
nearing the end of the year ♪</i>

46:52.022 --> 46:57.933
♪<i>♪ And time for the season
of joy and such good cheer ♪</i>

47:00.004 --> 47:03.545
♪<i>♪ This time when we set aside ♪</i>

47:03.679 --> 47:07.619
♪<i>♪ All feelings
that cause divide ♪</i>

47:07.753 --> 47:13.163
♪<i>♪ And bring us together
in peace and love ♪</i>

47:15.434 --> 47:20.612
♪<i>♪ It oughta be
Christmas every day ♪</i>

47:21.981 --> 47:23.484
♪<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

47:23.618 --> 47:25.856
♪<i>♪ There oughta be
snow and lights ♪</i>

47:25.989 --> 47:29.764
♪<i>♪ and Santa on his sleigh ♪</i>

47:29.898 --> 47:33.437
♪<i>♪ And when the sleigh
bells start to ring ♪</i>

47:33.572 --> 47:37.244
♪<i>♪ And all the children
start to sing ♪</i>

47:37.378 --> 47:43.490
♪<i>♪ Oh, it oughta be
Christmas every day ♪</i>

47:44.927 --> 47:47.365
♪<i>♪ Ooo ♪</i>

47:47.498 --> 47:53.644
♪<i>♪ It oughta be
Christmas every day ♪</i>

47:59.690 --> 48:01.159
[Mary sighs]

48:03.698 --> 48:05.100
So, you nervous?

48:06.170 --> 48:07.205
Nervous about what?

48:07.338 --> 48:08.908
[Mary] Your interview.

48:09.042 --> 48:11.112
No, I'll be fine.

48:13.050 --> 48:14.887
I'll be fine, right?

48:15.020 --> 48:16.557
You'll be great.

48:16.691 --> 48:18.562
And I happen to be really good
at putting people at ease.

48:18.695 --> 48:20.297
Yeah, so I've noticed.

48:24.607 --> 48:26.578
I do have a favor to ask.

48:26.711 --> 48:27.946
[Blake] <i>Oh?</i>

48:28.949 --> 48:30.284
I don't want Lexi there.

48:32.354 --> 48:34.125
She's the Vice
President of Marketing.

48:34.259 --> 48:37.097
She's a distraction,
and I do not need

48:37.231 --> 48:39.837
or want her looking over
my shoulder all day.

48:39.971 --> 48:41.340
[Blake sighs]

48:41.473 --> 48:42.509
Okay.

48:42.876 --> 48:44.045
Okay?

48:44.179 --> 48:46.584
Okay, I'll tell
her to stand down.

48:49.155 --> 48:50.424
Thank you.

48:52.696 --> 48:55.903
So, what happens after you
filmed everything you need?

48:56.838 --> 49:02.114
Hmm, go back to the city
and put it all together.

49:03.117 --> 49:04.553
And that's it.

49:05.254 --> 49:06.423
[Mary] <i>That's it?</i>

49:06.558 --> 49:07.458
[Mary giggles]

49:07.593 --> 49:08.895
That's a lot.

49:09.029 --> 49:11.634
No, I mean that's
it for Brunswick?

49:11.768 --> 49:15.107
[soft, jazzy music]

49:15.240 --> 49:17.478
Yeah, it is.

49:19.015 --> 49:20.552
That's too bad.

49:27.365 --> 49:29.804
You know, I did enjoy it here

49:29.937 --> 49:31.741
a lot more than I
thought I would.

49:31.875 --> 49:33.945
Yeah, no, me too.

49:34.079 --> 49:36.282
I mean, having you here.

49:40.023 --> 49:44.833
And I won't say it wasn't
great getting to know you.

49:45.735 --> 49:51.145
But you have a life and
a job back in Chicago.

49:52.649 --> 49:56.390
And you have an entire
family legacy to continue.

49:56.524 --> 49:57.559
Yeah.

50:00.965 --> 50:02.903
Another time, another place.

50:03.036 --> 50:04.171
Yeah.

50:20.204 --> 50:22.341
[phone beeps]

50:27.919 --> 50:28.888
Hello?

50:29.022 --> 50:30.290
[Brianna] <i>You were asleep?</i>

50:30.424 --> 50:31.794
[Mary] <i>Yeah, I
guess I needed it.</i>

50:31.928 --> 50:34.166
Sounds like the country
life agrees with you.

50:34.299 --> 50:35.535
It was just a late night.

50:35.669 --> 50:36.904
[Brianna] <i>See, I love that.</i>

50:37.038 --> 50:38.140
I love that for you.

50:38.273 --> 50:39.844
<i>Okay, now tell me everything.</i>

50:39.977 --> 50:41.113
How's the toy farmer?

50:41.246 --> 50:42.348
Blake.

50:42.481 --> 50:44.586
[Brianna gasps]
He has a name.

50:44.720 --> 50:46.122
Blake, <i>yes.</i>

50:46.256 --> 50:50.030
Yeah, he's a really great guy.

50:50.164 --> 50:52.970
But I just think
it's bad timing.

50:53.103 --> 50:54.105
Oh, who cares about timing?

50:54.238 --> 50:57.078
I mean, can't he leave Iowa?

50:57.211 --> 50:59.282
No, girl, he's not leaving.

50:59.415 --> 51:01.353
He has roots here.

51:01.486 --> 51:04.425
Would you, gasp, move there?

51:04.560 --> 51:06.163
No, no.

51:06.296 --> 51:07.766
I have spent <i>way too many years</i>

51:07.900 --> 51:09.402
<i>working my way up
that network ladder.</i>

51:09.536 --> 51:11.674
<i>It would be so
stupid to leave now.</i>

51:11.808 --> 51:14.345
And this story is
just so much better

51:14.479 --> 51:15.682
than I ever could
have imagined.

51:15.815 --> 51:17.919
I think I'm just
<i>getting caught up in it.</i>

51:18.053 --> 51:19.455
<i>I think that's all it is.</i>

51:19.590 --> 51:21.894
He's part of the
story, you know?

51:22.027 --> 51:24.967
Mary, what about your story?

51:25.100 --> 51:26.303
[Mary chuckles]

51:26.436 --> 51:27.973
It's just complicated.

51:28.106 --> 51:29.375
Is it?

51:29.510 --> 51:31.413
[Mary chuckles]
How's my bathroom?

51:31.547 --> 51:32.816
[Brianna] <i>It's fine.</i>

51:33.852 --> 51:35.287
I think the guys
left early for lunch,

51:35.421 --> 51:36.590
'cause I was talking too much.

51:36.724 --> 51:38.627
Oh, I'm sure
that's not happening.

51:38.761 --> 51:40.230
Look, I'm coming home tomorrow,

51:40.363 --> 51:43.169
so just call me if
anything explodes, okay?

51:43.303 --> 51:45.408
You'll be the second
person I call, bye.

51:45.542 --> 51:47.211
- [phone beeps]
- Bye.

51:51.186 --> 51:53.189
Okay, I gotta get up.

51:57.365 --> 52:00.237
[bright music]

52:13.598 --> 52:15.167
[Mary] You know what?

52:15.300 --> 52:17.237
I interviewed Alton
behind his desk.

52:17.371 --> 52:19.208
I don't wanna do the
same thing with you.

52:19.342 --> 52:23.885
It's too similar, so I
think we'll put you here.

52:24.018 --> 52:26.089
Okay, whatever you say.

52:26.591 --> 52:28.661
Sorry, Mary, give me a minute.

52:29.228 --> 52:30.565
The colors on the
monitor are off.

52:30.699 --> 52:33.036
Plus, I still need to mic him.

52:33.170 --> 52:34.405
Okay, you know, I can mic him.

52:34.540 --> 52:35.875
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

52:36.945 --> 52:37.980
Thanks.

52:38.480 --> 52:40.183
Could you stand up, please?

52:42.322 --> 52:46.129
And I'm gonna go ahead and just
slide this down your shirt.

52:46.263 --> 52:48.333
[soft, tender music]

52:48.467 --> 52:51.239
You can grab it on the bottom.

52:58.955 --> 53:01.693
And you can just put
that in your pocket.

53:05.334 --> 53:06.804
And have a seat.

53:11.748 --> 53:13.150
- All right.
- [camera beeps]

53:13.283 --> 53:14.620
Speeding.

53:14.754 --> 53:16.524
Okay, so just remember
what we talked about.

53:16.657 --> 53:19.763
Look at me, don't look at the
camera, no one-word answers,

53:19.897 --> 53:23.303
and try and rephrase the
question in your answer.

53:23.436 --> 53:25.340
Rephrase, right,
right, got it.

53:25.474 --> 53:27.244
So, why don't we start talking

53:27.377 --> 53:28.981
a little bit about craftsmanship.

53:29.115 --> 53:32.255
Why is craftsmanship so
important to Johnson Toys?

53:33.190 --> 53:36.597
Craftsmanship is important
to Johnson Toys because,

53:38.233 --> 53:39.804
[Blake clears throat]

53:39.937 --> 53:43.878
Craftsmanship is important to
Johnson Toys because, well,

53:46.851 --> 53:48.453
look, I'm sorry, could we start

53:48.588 --> 53:50.024
with something a little easier,

53:50.157 --> 53:52.996
like what do we manufacture,
things like that?

53:53.130 --> 53:54.666
We already got that with Alton,

53:54.800 --> 53:57.004
but it's okay, just relax.

53:57.137 --> 53:58.073
I'm trying.

53:58.207 --> 53:59.743
[Mary giggles]

53:59.877 --> 54:03.718
Pretend that we're at dinner,
just like the other night.

54:04.653 --> 54:08.460
Speak from your heart
and just tell me,

54:09.295 --> 54:11.032
why is craftsmanship
so important?

54:16.142 --> 54:19.081
My grandfather, the
founder of Johnson Toys,

54:19.215 --> 54:23.625
he always said, "Anything worth
doing is worth doing right."

54:23.758 --> 54:25.795
- [Mary giggles]
- [Blake chuckles]

54:25.928 --> 54:28.466
I know, I know, millions of
people say the same thing.

54:28.601 --> 54:30.739
But I don't know
how many of 'em

54:30.872 --> 54:33.109
actually live it, you know?

54:33.544 --> 54:35.515
'Cause to him, craftsmanship

54:35.648 --> 54:37.284
wasn't just about
doing your best work,

54:37.418 --> 54:40.592
it was about
allowing other people

54:40.725 --> 54:43.396
to see the greatness
within themselves.

54:44.734 --> 54:45.902
That was really great, Blake.

54:46.035 --> 54:47.171
[Mary chuckles]

54:47.973 --> 54:52.782
So, Johnson Toys could
manufacture whatever it chooses.

54:52.916 --> 54:55.287
Why focus on Christmas items?

54:55.789 --> 54:58.260
All right, please don't
take this outta context,

54:58.393 --> 55:01.600
but you know what
drives me crazy,

55:01.734 --> 55:05.642
is that for so many people,
it's all about the money.

55:05.775 --> 55:09.583
That's what Christmas
is about, the money.

55:11.587 --> 55:12.722
Not for me.

55:14.693 --> 55:16.162
What's it about for you?

55:17.131 --> 55:20.170
They say Christmas is the
happiest day of the year.

55:20.304 --> 55:25.480
Well, we'd like to bring that
spirit to the other 364 days.

55:25.615 --> 55:26.917
[Mary giggles]

55:28.420 --> 55:29.656
Great.

55:32.494 --> 55:34.098
Ah, there you are.

55:34.232 --> 55:35.167
I was looking all over for you.

55:35.301 --> 55:36.336
Hey.

55:36.469 --> 55:37.739
Everything okay?

55:38.507 --> 55:39.743
Yeah.

55:41.547 --> 55:42.915
Are you not happy
with the interview?

55:43.049 --> 55:45.420
'Cause, I mean, Crash
said I was pretty good.

55:45.555 --> 55:46.857
[Mary giggles]

55:46.990 --> 55:49.730
Oh wow, he was just
being nice, wasn't he?

55:50.163 --> 55:51.734
Crash wouldn't do that.

55:52.301 --> 55:54.438
Okay, then what is it?

55:54.573 --> 55:56.442
You were amazing.

55:57.579 --> 55:59.181
Well, I guess I was just lucky

55:59.315 --> 56:01.319
that I had someone that
could put me at ease.

56:01.754 --> 56:05.493
[soft, jazzy piano music]

56:07.532 --> 56:11.005
Just remember our
deal, all right?

56:11.607 --> 56:12.942
The real story.

56:13.644 --> 56:14.913
Real story.

56:17.653 --> 56:19.054
Look, I hate to throw you out,

56:19.188 --> 56:21.526
but I got some work to do.

56:22.896 --> 56:24.600
Maybe if you're free later,

56:24.733 --> 56:28.473
we could get some dinner,
just to say goodbye?

56:29.375 --> 56:31.045
I think I can fit you in.

56:32.248 --> 56:33.884
- Okay.
- Sure.

56:34.018 --> 56:35.053
See ya.

56:39.028 --> 56:40.463
[Mary sighs]

56:42.803 --> 56:44.973
[Crash] Sure you don't wanna
ride back to the inn?

56:45.407 --> 56:46.944
Nah, I feel like walking.

56:47.512 --> 56:48.814
[Crash] You know,
I had my doubts

56:48.948 --> 56:50.685
about all this,
just like you did.

56:50.818 --> 56:53.023
But the truth is, it's turning
out to be a nice piece.

56:53.156 --> 56:55.126
[Mary chuckles]
Get outta here.

56:56.229 --> 56:57.865
- See ya.
- See ya.

56:58.801 --> 57:00.303
♪ Ever wonder what it's like ♪

57:00.437 --> 57:05.848
♪<i>♪ To only wanna
be in one place ♪</i>

57:07.184 --> 57:09.254
♪<i>♪ When any and everything ♪</i>

57:09.388 --> 57:15.134
♪<i>♪ Reminds you of the
sweet smile on that face ♪</i>

57:15.568 --> 57:18.641
♪<i>♪ A smile with enough sunshine ♪</i>

57:18.775 --> 57:23.584
♪<i>♪ To bring a snowman
to its knees ♪</i>

57:24.351 --> 57:27.526
♪<i>♪ There's something
in the air ♪</i>

57:27.659 --> 57:30.565
♪<i>♪ That makes me wanna make ♪</i>

57:30.698 --> 57:33.704
♪<i>♪ More memories with you ♪</i>

57:36.042 --> 57:38.714
Mary, how long
have you been there?

57:38.848 --> 57:40.652
Not long, I'm
just on my way out.

57:40.785 --> 57:41.887
Oh, can I fix you something?

57:42.021 --> 57:43.557
[Mary] <i>No, no, no, thank you.</i>

57:43.691 --> 57:44.860
I have plans.

57:44.993 --> 57:48.133
Plans? Here,
in Brunswick, Iowa?

57:48.266 --> 57:49.836
I make friends easily.

57:50.304 --> 57:51.238
Touche.

57:51.974 --> 57:53.076
Mm-hmm.

57:53.209 --> 57:54.478
Can I get you guys
anything while I'm out?

57:54.613 --> 57:56.383
We're fine, dear.
You have fun.

57:56.517 --> 57:57.852
Okay.

57:57.986 --> 58:00.057
We don't lock doors here,
so come back whenever.

58:00.191 --> 58:01.158
Thanks.

58:01.292 --> 58:02.328
Goodnight.

58:02.461 --> 58:04.097
♪<i>♪ Laughter and relaxing ♪</i>

58:04.231 --> 58:08.172
♪<i>♪ These memories
are all we need ♪</i>

58:08.306 --> 58:13.650
♪<i>♪ If you only have right
now and right here ♪</i>

58:14.519 --> 58:15.955
- Hey.
- Hi.

58:16.089 --> 58:17.558
[Mary giggles]

58:20.464 --> 58:21.633
You look great.

58:21.767 --> 58:22.969
So do you.

58:23.103 --> 58:25.074
Oh, hey, Blake, we're slammed.

58:25.207 --> 58:26.109
Gimme a minute?

58:26.242 --> 58:27.846
Take your time,
we're in no rush.

58:27.980 --> 58:29.415
You want something to
drink while you wait?

58:29.549 --> 58:30.283
I'm good.

58:30.417 --> 58:31.554
Mary, rye?

58:31.687 --> 58:32.689
No, thanks.

58:32.823 --> 58:34.693
[Mary and Roberta chuckle]

58:34.827 --> 58:36.162
You know, I'm really starting

58:36.295 --> 58:38.032
to like how people
know my name here.

58:38.166 --> 58:41.339
Aw, you're gonna miss
our small town hospitality.

58:41.472 --> 58:42.776
I am.

58:42.909 --> 58:45.014
Speaking of which, how's
Bernice treating you?

58:45.147 --> 58:47.652
She's so sweet, I
want her to adopt me.

58:47.786 --> 58:48.554
Careful what you wish for.

58:48.688 --> 58:49.690
[Mary giggles]

58:49.823 --> 58:51.459
Oh, looks like we're ready.

58:52.294 --> 58:53.998
So, my next piece is
on the Transit Authority

58:54.131 --> 58:55.601
and how the bidding process

58:55.734 --> 58:57.037
is not transparent
to the public.

58:57.170 --> 58:58.373
Sure.

58:58.507 --> 58:59.576
So, this makes for
potentially criminal behavior,

58:59.709 --> 59:00.945
and even if it doesn't,

59:01.078 --> 59:02.615
it foments distrust
of the government.

59:02.749 --> 59:05.020
Wow, that sounds
like quite the expose.

59:05.153 --> 59:06.891
It's important
for people to see.

59:07.024 --> 59:08.627
Making a difference, right?

59:08.761 --> 59:10.030
That's right.

59:10.632 --> 59:11.867
So, the interview
must have gone well,

59:12.000 --> 59:14.439
if it turned into a date.
[Lexi chuckles]

59:14.573 --> 59:15.641
<i>I'm kidding.</i>

59:15.775 --> 59:18.280
Seriously though, how'd it go?

59:18.413 --> 59:19.749
It was fine.

59:20.652 --> 59:21.954
I recall you using the words,

59:22.087 --> 59:25.728
"you," and "were,"
and "amazing."

59:25.862 --> 59:28.333
It was a very good interview.

59:28.466 --> 59:29.969
I got exactly what I needed.

59:30.705 --> 59:32.508
I'm thrilled to hear it.

59:32.976 --> 59:35.615
What else do you need
for your story, Mary?

59:35.748 --> 59:37.117
Blake was the last holdout,

59:37.251 --> 59:40.691
so as of a few hours
ago, we're wrapped.

59:41.392 --> 59:44.164
Heading back to
Chicago, then, huh?

59:44.298 --> 59:45.768
Yeah, I guess so.

59:46.502 --> 59:49.509
Well, we're all gonna
be so sad to see you go.

59:49.642 --> 59:50.945
[Mary] <i>Thanks.</i>

59:51.078 --> 59:52.481
[Lexi] <i>Well, I don't
wanna intrude,</i>

59:52.615 --> 59:55.086
I just wanted to make sure
everything went great.

59:55.922 --> 59:57.457
Glad to hear it did.

59:58.025 --> 59:59.394
Have a good night.

01:00:00.531 --> 01:00:03.336
So, where were we?

01:00:04.405 --> 01:00:06.577
Making a difference, yeah?

01:00:06.710 --> 01:00:07.444
Yeah.

01:00:07.579 --> 01:00:08.848
[Mary giggles]

01:00:08.981 --> 01:00:10.918
Sorry, one second.

01:00:11.821 --> 01:00:13.758
[phone buzzes]

01:00:13.891 --> 01:00:15.427
It's my foreman,
I need to take this.

01:00:15.562 --> 01:00:17.030
Please, yeah.

01:00:17.164 --> 01:00:18.065
Yep.

01:00:19.202 --> 01:00:20.236
[Blake sighs]

01:00:20.370 --> 01:00:21.907
No, I understand.

01:00:22.909 --> 01:00:24.178
See you soon.

01:00:26.884 --> 01:00:28.754
The assembly line
is down again.

01:00:29.255 --> 01:00:29.923
What's that mean?

01:00:30.057 --> 01:00:31.025
It means I gotta go.

01:00:31.158 --> 01:00:32.862
- Oh.
- I'm sorry.

01:00:33.396 --> 01:00:34.633
That's too bad.

01:00:35.067 --> 01:00:37.705
I know it sounds dramatic,
but Christmas is on the line.

01:00:37.839 --> 01:00:38.674
[Mary giggles]

01:00:38.807 --> 01:00:39.810
Santa and those elves--

01:00:39.943 --> 01:00:42.248
Can't do it all themselves.

01:00:42.381 --> 01:00:43.382
Yeah.

01:00:43.517 --> 01:00:44.686
[soft, tender piano music]

01:00:44.820 --> 01:00:46.155
[Mary giggles]

01:00:47.559 --> 01:00:50.297
Well, if this is goodbye,

01:00:51.399 --> 01:00:56.375
it was so nice to meet you,
and thank you for everything.

01:00:57.478 --> 01:01:00.116
No, yeah, it's been great.

01:01:00.250 --> 01:01:01.151
Thank you.

01:01:02.287 --> 01:01:03.189
Yeah.

01:01:04.659 --> 01:01:06.530
Goodbye, Mr. Johnson.

01:01:06.664 --> 01:01:08.333
Goodbye, Ms. Romero.

01:01:08.466 --> 01:01:13.844
♪<i>♪ I was hoping you'd fly
south with the birds ♪</i>

01:01:15.515 --> 01:01:16.516
Bye.

01:01:16.650 --> 01:01:17.853
Bye.

01:01:17.986 --> 01:01:21.058
♪<i>♪ But hey, that's nothing new ♪</i>

01:01:21.192 --> 01:01:24.933
♪<i>♪ What feels different
now is I'm spending ♪</i>

01:01:25.066 --> 01:01:26.670
Hey, I don't think I'm, oh.

01:01:26.804 --> 01:01:28.106
Did Blake have to leave?

01:01:28.239 --> 01:01:31.378
Yeah, something went
wrong at the factory, so.

01:01:32.147 --> 01:01:34.084
He tried, you know.

01:01:34.752 --> 01:01:36.289
- I'm sorry?
- In the city.

01:01:36.422 --> 01:01:38.159
He tried to sell his
paintings in Chicago,

01:01:38.292 --> 01:01:40.464
even opened a little store.

01:01:40.598 --> 01:01:41.900
They just never sold.

01:01:42.033 --> 01:01:44.104
His grandfather's paintings?

01:01:45.140 --> 01:01:46.644
Is that what he told you?

01:01:47.712 --> 01:01:52.656
♪<i>♪ But you brought back that
feeling that melted away ♪</i>

01:01:52.789 --> 01:01:54.124
Why are you telling me this?

01:01:54.526 --> 01:01:56.596
Maybe to save
you some heartache.

01:01:57.397 --> 01:01:59.703
- I can take care of myself.
- Please, Mary.

01:02:00.170 --> 01:02:02.140
Blake is amazing,
and we all love him.

01:02:02.274 --> 01:02:05.247
But if he can't face the past

01:02:05.380 --> 01:02:07.785
or his own failures,
how's he ever gonna grow,

01:02:07.918 --> 01:02:10.691
be the leader that
Johnson Toys needs?

01:02:10.825 --> 01:02:13.898
Maybe he needs some encouragement,

01:02:14.031 --> 01:02:15.901
or the right support?

01:02:16.703 --> 01:02:18.005
Yeah, maybe.

01:02:18.807 --> 01:02:20.511
Guess we'll never know.

01:02:22.849 --> 01:02:25.320
Well, safe travels.

01:02:25.453 --> 01:02:26.890
Mm-hmm, thanks.

01:02:27.024 --> 01:02:32.200
♪<i>♪ Just to look at lights
and feel anything at all ♪</i>

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:37.912
♪<i>♪ I can't find the cold,
but every year that's true ♪</i>

01:02:38.947 --> 01:02:45.027
♪<i>♪ It just got warmer now that
I'm sitting here with you ♪</i>

01:02:45.929 --> 01:02:51.806
♪<i>♪ And no matter what,
every year feels the same ♪</i>

01:02:52.542 --> 01:02:54.311
This is ridiculous.

01:02:54.444 --> 01:02:58.352
♪<i>♪ But you brought back that
feeling that melted away ♪</i>

01:03:00.023 --> 01:03:06.770
♪<i>♪ Something's been missing,
but this year, it changed ♪</i>

01:03:07.872 --> 01:03:12.815
♪<i>♪ And now, Christmas
doesn't feel so far away ♪</i>

01:03:12.949 --> 01:03:15.688
[door knocks]

01:03:15.822 --> 01:03:19.494
[soft, tender piano music]

01:03:25.908 --> 01:03:27.945
- Hi.
- Hi.

01:03:29.481 --> 01:03:31.586
Everything okay
at the factory?

01:03:32.888 --> 01:03:34.224
That's why you're here?

01:03:34.358 --> 01:03:35.259
No.

01:03:36.362 --> 01:03:37.965
I don't know, I can't sleep.

01:03:38.399 --> 01:03:41.105
Yeah, that makes two of us.

01:03:43.342 --> 01:03:46.014
I have one more question
I need to ask you.

01:03:47.685 --> 01:03:48.587
Okay.

01:03:49.555 --> 01:03:50.557
Come inside.

01:03:53.229 --> 01:03:55.133
Fire, something to drink?

01:03:55.868 --> 01:03:58.105
Coffee, if you have it.

01:04:01.913 --> 01:04:04.451
[soft music]

01:04:06.088 --> 01:04:07.357
Here you go.

01:04:07.491 --> 01:04:08.527
Thanks.

01:04:08.660 --> 01:04:10.396
So, what's your question?

01:04:11.098 --> 01:04:12.969
- Were you gonna tell me?
- Tell you what?

01:04:13.103 --> 01:04:14.972
That all these
are your paintings.

01:04:18.079 --> 01:04:19.248
Not all of them.

01:04:19.381 --> 01:04:21.920
A few are my grandpa's.

01:04:22.054 --> 01:04:24.024
Well, they're really similar.

01:04:24.157 --> 01:04:26.228
Yeah, well, I
adopted his style,

01:04:26.361 --> 01:04:28.265
and I added a little
flair of my own.

01:04:28.399 --> 01:04:31.138
It's just too bad I
didn't inherit his talent.

01:04:31.272 --> 01:04:33.143
They have a ton of talent.

01:04:33.644 --> 01:04:34.980
Did you ever sell any?

01:04:35.113 --> 01:04:39.121
A few, here and there,
but not enough to ever--

01:04:39.254 --> 01:04:42.127
To keep a gallery
open in Chicago?

01:04:42.629 --> 01:04:43.897
Yeah, I know.

01:04:44.933 --> 01:04:47.004
Let me guess, Lexi?

01:04:47.137 --> 01:04:48.573
Is it true?

01:04:48.707 --> 01:04:50.009
Is it true that I once
opened a gallery in Chicago,

01:04:50.143 --> 01:04:52.615
and that I don't
own it anymore?

01:04:52.748 --> 01:04:54.217
Yeah, it's true.

01:04:55.220 --> 01:04:56.488
What happened?

01:04:56.623 --> 01:04:58.460
You're leaving tomorrow,
what does it matter?

01:04:58.594 --> 01:04:59.696
You lied.

01:04:59.829 --> 01:05:00.765
[Blake] <i>I omitted.</i>

01:05:00.898 --> 01:05:02.033
Same thing.

01:05:02.534 --> 01:05:04.839
I answered the
questions you asked me.

01:05:04.973 --> 01:05:07.846
I participated in your piece
to the best of my abilities.

01:05:07.979 --> 01:05:09.181
I see.

01:05:11.218 --> 01:05:12.788
Listen, I'm exhausted.

01:05:13.255 --> 01:05:17.097
We work farm hours here,
so I gotta be up soon.

01:05:17.231 --> 01:05:19.669
Yeah, absolutely.

01:05:20.705 --> 01:05:22.373
I better get going.

01:05:24.311 --> 01:05:25.581
Look forward to
seeing the story.

01:05:25.714 --> 01:05:27.016
[Mary] <i>Mm-hmm.</i>

01:05:27.150 --> 01:05:31.458
[lush, emotional
orchestra music]

01:05:37.104 --> 01:05:38.339
Good morning, Mary.

01:05:38.472 --> 01:05:39.810
How'd you sleep?

01:05:39.943 --> 01:05:41.445
Okay, you know.

01:05:41.580 --> 01:05:44.251
It wasn't the room's
fault, though.

01:05:44.852 --> 01:05:46.388
You're up early.

01:05:46.523 --> 01:05:48.994
Yeah, I thought I'd get
a head start on the day.

01:05:49.128 --> 01:05:50.497
You heading home?

01:05:50.631 --> 01:05:51.533
I am.

01:05:51.667 --> 01:05:52.500
Are you?

01:05:53.703 --> 01:05:56.142
You know, I've been in
this business a long time.

01:05:56.275 --> 01:05:58.279
Some might say, too long.

01:05:58.413 --> 01:05:59.415
No.

01:05:59.549 --> 01:06:02.955
So, I thought I'd
stay here for a while.

01:06:03.089 --> 01:06:04.325
On the house.

01:06:04.458 --> 01:06:06.461
Oh, well Bernice,
you need to watch out,

01:06:06.596 --> 01:06:09.769
because this one here
is a shameless charmer.

01:06:09.903 --> 01:06:11.438
I got that feeling.

01:06:11.573 --> 01:06:14.010
She'll probably get tired
of me before Christmas.

01:06:14.612 --> 01:06:17.417
From what Crash tells me,
this place and the folks here

01:06:17.552 --> 01:06:20.022
have a tendency
to grow on people.

01:06:20.156 --> 01:06:22.327
People you'd least expect.

01:06:22.862 --> 01:06:23.831
Yeah.

01:06:24.331 --> 01:06:25.768
Did you tell Hank?

01:06:26.302 --> 01:06:28.841
Not yet, I'll wait
until after the holidays.

01:06:28.974 --> 01:06:30.043
Okay.

01:06:30.176 --> 01:06:31.478
Okay, great.

01:06:31.613 --> 01:06:33.383
Well, this is a lot
for me right now.

01:06:33.517 --> 01:06:37.090
So Bernice, if I could just
settle up, I'll get on my way.

01:06:37.224 --> 01:06:38.994
You won't be a
stranger, will you?

01:06:39.128 --> 01:06:40.697
You know, I have
enjoyed it here,

01:06:40.831 --> 01:06:44.238
but I honestly don't know
how often I'll be back.

01:06:44.371 --> 01:06:45.707
Except for, probably,

01:06:45.841 --> 01:06:48.479
the 50th anniversary
of the Mistletoads.

01:06:48.613 --> 01:06:51.419
Well, good luck
with the story.

01:06:51.553 --> 01:06:53.623
Everyone is so
excited to see it.

01:06:53.757 --> 01:06:54.759
Thank you.

01:06:54.892 --> 01:06:55.794
Thank you for everything.

01:06:55.928 --> 01:06:57.030
[Bernice] <i>You're welcome.</i>

01:06:57.163 --> 01:06:58.266
Crash.

01:06:58.399 --> 01:07:01.405
[playful, bright music]

01:07:06.281 --> 01:07:09.421
[soft piano music]

01:07:18.172 --> 01:07:18.941
- <i>Cheers.</i>
- <i>Cheers.</i>

01:07:19.074 --> 01:07:20.443
[glasses clink]

01:07:20.578 --> 01:07:23.082
It is about time we
made this happen, finally.

01:07:23.216 --> 01:07:25.086
I know, I'm so sorry,
it's all my fault.

01:07:25.220 --> 01:07:26.488
I just had a really busy year.

01:07:26.623 --> 01:07:29.962
Mmm, Mary is the
busiest, the coolest,

01:07:30.096 --> 01:07:32.902
and the prettiest
person I know, okay?

01:07:33.035 --> 01:07:34.204
Yeah, you're a
reporter, right?

01:07:34.338 --> 01:07:35.707
I am, yes.

01:07:35.841 --> 01:07:37.678
I actually just finished
a story about this company

01:07:37.812 --> 01:07:39.782
in Iowa that manufactures
Christmas items.

01:07:39.916 --> 01:07:43.256
But the real story, it's
actually about the town

01:07:43.389 --> 01:07:44.926
more than it is the company.

01:07:45.059 --> 01:07:46.763
Cool, like a charity piece.

01:07:46.896 --> 01:07:49.168
No, no, not a charity piece.

01:07:49.301 --> 01:07:51.372
Right, so I'm not sure
if Brianna told you,

01:07:51.506 --> 01:07:53.777
but Dylan and I
are in real estate.

01:07:53.910 --> 01:07:55.246
Yeah, she mentioned that.

01:07:55.379 --> 01:07:57.117
We're working on a
huge project right now.

01:07:57.250 --> 01:07:58.419
It could be a game-changer.

01:07:58.553 --> 01:07:59.922
- Okay.
- <i>And you know,</i>

01:08:00.056 --> 01:08:01.660
<i>if those investors
really come through,</i>

01:08:01.793 --> 01:08:02.962
<i>we could bid on that
riverfront property</i>

01:08:03.096 --> 01:08:03.931
<i>as early as next quarter.</i>

01:08:04.064 --> 01:08:05.635
[Todd] <i>Properties.</i>

01:08:05.768 --> 01:08:07.236
<i>Remember, we don't wanna
limit this to the riverfront.</i>

01:08:07.370 --> 01:08:08.740
[Dylan] <i>Absolutely,
properties.</i>

01:08:08.874 --> 01:08:10.377
<i>I'm not the one you
need to convince.</i>

01:08:10.511 --> 01:08:11.311
<i>I still think we
should do commercial.</i>

01:08:11.445 --> 01:08:13.717
[voices murmur and echo]

01:08:19.996 --> 01:08:21.132
Hey, what's up?

01:08:21.265 --> 01:08:22.935
Oh, thanks for swinging by.

01:08:23.069 --> 01:08:24.137
Coffee?

01:08:24.271 --> 01:08:25.741
- No, thanks.
- We gotta talk.

01:08:25.874 --> 01:08:27.545
You know the Transit
Authority bidding scheme story?

01:08:27.678 --> 01:08:29.014
It's really starting
to heat up, so--

01:08:29.147 --> 01:08:30.751
I wanna talk
Brunswick, Johnson Toys.

01:08:30.885 --> 01:08:33.624
I watched your cut,
I had Phil show me.

01:08:33.757 --> 01:08:34.959
It's not done yet.

01:08:35.092 --> 01:08:36.963
I think we should just
wait until I fine-tune it.

01:08:37.097 --> 01:08:38.399
Come on, Mary, don't spin me.

01:08:38.533 --> 01:08:39.669
I've been doing
this a long time.

01:08:39.802 --> 01:08:41.271
I know how to
watch a rough cut,

01:08:41.405 --> 01:08:43.009
and I can see where
you're taking the story.

01:08:43.142 --> 01:08:44.746
But that is the
real story, okay?

01:08:44.880 --> 01:08:47.250
It's an artist who sacrifices
his dream to save a small town

01:08:47.384 --> 01:08:50.557
and then becomes one of the
biggest employers in the state.

01:08:50.691 --> 01:08:52.728
I'm taking over, I had
Phil start a new cut.

01:08:52.861 --> 01:08:55.066
Hank, you promised
me creative control.

01:08:55.199 --> 01:08:57.938
Look, I like what you did
with the Christmas paintings,

01:08:58.072 --> 01:08:59.609
and the old man
building up the company

01:08:59.742 --> 01:09:01.445
so the son has
something to inherit.

01:09:01.579 --> 01:09:03.015
But you missed the brief.

01:09:03.149 --> 01:09:05.319
You were supposed to be
there for the Mistletoads.

01:09:05.453 --> 01:09:07.925
This story is actually
very important to me,

01:09:08.059 --> 01:09:10.564
and I made promises to the
people who participated.

01:09:10.697 --> 01:09:12.167
What do you want me to say?

01:09:12.300 --> 01:09:13.637
I've got bosses,
too, and right now,

01:09:13.771 --> 01:09:15.741
they're more concerned
with the bottom line.

01:09:16.543 --> 01:09:17.945
I gave them my word.

01:09:20.651 --> 01:09:22.187
It's not gonna be that bad.

01:09:22.320 --> 01:09:23.590
I know what I'm doing, okay?

01:09:23.723 --> 01:09:25.259
The piece airs in two days.

01:09:25.393 --> 01:09:27.097
So, why don't you just go home

01:09:27.230 --> 01:09:29.668
and have yourself
a great Christmas.

01:09:31.238 --> 01:09:32.608
[Hank sighs]

01:09:33.843 --> 01:09:36.783
[soft piano music]

01:09:37.651 --> 01:09:38.720
Thanks for coming over.

01:09:38.854 --> 01:09:40.089
Of course.

01:09:40.222 --> 01:09:41.993
- Happy to be here.
- You excited?

01:09:42.127 --> 01:09:43.162
We'll see.

01:09:43.296 --> 01:09:44.164
I'm so proud of you.

01:09:44.298 --> 01:09:45.868
Thank you.

01:09:46.001 --> 01:09:48.205
[grand orchestra music]

01:09:51.279 --> 01:09:53.950
<i>Chances are you've got
something made by Johnson Toys</i>

01:09:54.084 --> 01:09:57.124
<i>among your holiday
decorations, or under the tree.</i>

01:09:57.257 --> 01:09:58.660
<i>And if you're of a certain age,</i>

01:09:58.793 --> 01:10:00.664
<i>you probably remember
this festive frog,</i>

01:10:00.798 --> 01:10:02.568
<i>whose 40th anniversary
is this year.</i>

01:10:02.701 --> 01:10:04.471
[Alton] <i>It's all about
the Mistletoads.</i>

01:10:04.605 --> 01:10:06.375
<i>He's my right-hand man.</i>

01:10:06.509 --> 01:10:07.712
[Alton chuckles]

01:10:07.845 --> 01:10:09.047
[News Anchor]
<i>With annual sales</i>

01:10:09.181 --> 01:10:10.784
<i>in the hundreds of millions,</i>

01:10:10.918 --> 01:10:12.554
<i>Johnson Toys of Brunswick,
Iowa is now the country's</i>

01:10:12.688 --> 01:10:15.962
<i>most successful purveyor
of Christmas trinkets.</i>

01:10:16.095 --> 01:10:17.932
<i>Thanks to some little
green helpers that had</i>

01:10:18.066 --> 01:10:21.639
<i>an adorable start, all
because of Alton's son, Blake.</i>

01:10:21.773 --> 01:10:24.110
<i>Blake would smash
words together</i>

01:10:24.244 --> 01:10:25.280
<i>when he was two or three,</i>

01:10:25.413 --> 01:10:26.916
<i>and when he saw some mistletoe</i>

01:10:27.050 --> 01:10:30.691
<i>hanging one day, he
shouted, "Mistletoad!"</i>

01:10:30.824 --> 01:10:32.060
[Alton chuckles]

01:10:32.194 --> 01:10:34.164
<i>We just thought it was
the funniest thing.</i>

01:10:34.297 --> 01:10:36.268
[Alton chuckles]

01:10:36.401 --> 01:10:37.938
<i>The rest is history.</i>

01:10:38.072 --> 01:10:39.642
[News Anchor] <i>Even though
Brunswick is a small town,</i>

01:10:39.775 --> 01:10:41.646
<i>it has cashed in big
on the Mistletoads.</i>

01:10:41.780 --> 01:10:44.484
[Roberta] <i>We created a special
drink, the Mistletoad.</i>

01:10:44.619 --> 01:10:45.921
<i>It's been really popular,</i>

01:10:46.054 --> 01:10:47.691
<i>we're actually keeping
it on the menu.</i>

01:10:47.825 --> 01:10:49.261
[News Anchor] <i>And what
about Blake Johnson,</i>

01:10:49.394 --> 01:10:50.463
<i>the little boy who
inspired it all?</i>

01:10:50.597 --> 01:10:52.334
<i>Does he still love Christmas?</i>

01:10:52.467 --> 01:10:55.574
<i>He now serves as Johnson Toys'
Vice President of Operations,</i>

01:10:55.708 --> 01:10:58.012
<i>and is focused on one thing.</i>

01:10:58.146 --> 01:10:59.481
<i>It is all about the money.</i>

01:11:00.216 --> 01:11:03.422
<i>That's what Christmas
is about, the money.</i>

01:11:04.023 --> 01:11:05.895
[News Reporter] <i>Well, when
you're as successful</i>

01:11:06.028 --> 01:11:07.396
<i>as Johnson Toys,</i>

01:11:07.531 --> 01:11:08.967
<i>Christmas would be
about money for me, too.</i>

01:11:09.100 --> 01:11:10.537
<i>Happy 40th, Mistletoads,</i>

01:11:10.671 --> 01:11:13.142
<i>and may you hop along
for decades to come.</i>

01:11:13.576 --> 01:11:15.313
Nicely done, Mary.

01:11:15.446 --> 01:11:16.950
[soft, sad piano music]

01:11:17.083 --> 01:11:17.952
What?

01:11:18.085 --> 01:11:20.123
I thought it was great.

01:11:20.256 --> 01:11:21.993
<i>It was great, right?</i>

01:11:22.126 --> 01:11:24.030
That was terrible.

01:11:24.164 --> 01:11:25.199
It wasn't that bad.

01:11:25.333 --> 01:11:26.335
Brianna.

01:11:26.468 --> 01:11:27.337
No, it wasn't bad at all.

01:11:27.470 --> 01:11:28.640
I think this is exactly

01:11:28.774 --> 01:11:29.942
the kind of stuff
you should be doing.

01:11:30.076 --> 01:11:31.278
I mean, this is what
people wanna see,

01:11:31.412 --> 01:11:33.215
especially around the holidays.

01:11:33.349 --> 01:11:35.386
That is not why
I got into this.

01:11:37.959 --> 01:11:39.394
[Dylan sighs]

01:11:39.528 --> 01:11:41.732
Okay, yeah, no problem.

01:11:44.304 --> 01:11:46.374
He is never gonna forgive me.

01:11:47.277 --> 01:11:48.478
I'm sorry.

01:11:49.882 --> 01:11:51.686
We'll get out of your hair.

01:11:52.487 --> 01:11:53.590
Thanks.

01:11:58.466 --> 01:12:01.739
[festive, sad music]

01:12:23.716 --> 01:12:25.854
[Alton] <i>Yes, yes.</i>

01:12:27.924 --> 01:12:29.328
<i>Well, that's
Christmas for you.</i>

01:12:29.461 --> 01:12:30.730
[Alton chuckles]

01:12:31.566 --> 01:12:32.901
<i>Okay, will do.</i>

01:12:35.507 --> 01:12:36.643
Thanks, Jim.

01:12:36.776 --> 01:12:39.080
Mary, it's so nice
to see you again.

01:12:39.214 --> 01:12:40.684
You, too. Um, is Blake--

01:12:40.818 --> 01:12:42.788
- I loved it.
- What?

01:12:42.922 --> 01:12:44.124
The piece.

01:12:44.257 --> 01:12:45.426
I already had my tech
people pull it off the air

01:12:45.561 --> 01:12:47.063
<i>and stream it on our site,</i>

01:12:47.196 --> 01:12:48.432
<i>or stream it off the
air, or whatever they do.</i>

01:12:48.566 --> 01:12:49.702
I can't thank you enough.

01:12:49.836 --> 01:12:51.606
It was so positive, so upbeat.

01:12:51.739 --> 01:12:53.209
It didn't take cheap shots.

01:12:53.342 --> 01:12:55.714
I'm making it mandatory
viewing for all our employees.

01:12:55.848 --> 01:12:58.185
Wow, well I'm glad
you liked it, I guess.

01:12:58.318 --> 01:13:00.691
Normally for us, Christmas
is done by December 15th,

01:13:00.824 --> 01:13:03.195
but with this story,
the orders are flying in.

01:13:03.329 --> 01:13:04.598
[phone rings]

01:13:04.732 --> 01:13:05.534
<i>Will you excuse me
just a second?</i>

01:13:05.668 --> 01:13:07.069
- Sure.
- Heya.

01:13:08.773 --> 01:13:10.143
I know, I know.

01:13:10.276 --> 01:13:11.011
[Alton chuckles]

01:13:11.145 --> 01:13:12.413
We're trying.

01:13:12.548 --> 01:13:14.551
Yeah, we've got
everything at capacity.

01:13:16.589 --> 01:13:17.924
Can we talk?

01:13:20.095 --> 01:13:21.699
Look, I didn't expect you
to be excited to see me,

01:13:21.833 --> 01:13:23.135
but I did come
all the way here.

01:13:23.268 --> 01:13:25.106
The least you could
do is let me explain.

01:13:25.240 --> 01:13:26.408
Explain what?

01:13:27.210 --> 01:13:28.479
How you used me?

01:13:29.247 --> 01:13:30.483
How you used everyone
in that piece

01:13:30.618 --> 01:13:31.586
to tell the story you wanted?

01:13:31.720 --> 01:13:32.922
It wasn't like that.

01:13:33.055 --> 01:13:34.793
I made our version,
the real story,

01:13:34.926 --> 01:13:36.662
and the station,
they took it over.

01:13:36.796 --> 01:13:40.002
The thing is, I'm
not even mad at you.

01:13:40.135 --> 01:13:41.405
[Blake chuckles]

01:13:41.539 --> 01:13:45.380
I'm mad at myself for trusting
you, caring about you.

01:13:45.514 --> 01:13:46.716
[Mary chuckles]

01:13:46.849 --> 01:13:48.218
I care about you, too.

01:13:48.352 --> 01:13:51.224
Well clearly, we value
different things, then.

01:13:52.761 --> 01:13:55.801
That piece, that made
us look so shallow.

01:13:56.268 --> 01:13:58.105
That wasn't about
my grandpa's legacy.

01:13:58.238 --> 01:13:59.274
No, I know that.

01:13:59.407 --> 01:14:01.211
But hey, my dad loves it.

01:14:01.913 --> 01:14:03.382
I'm sure he's gonna
spend a fortune

01:14:03.516 --> 01:14:05.286
on advertising
before he retires.

01:14:05.420 --> 01:14:06.523
He's retiring?

01:14:07.056 --> 01:14:08.392
[Blake] <i>This is his last Christmas.</i>

01:14:08.994 --> 01:14:10.597
He's gonna announce it at
the next board meeting.

01:14:11.164 --> 01:14:13.268
So, are you gonna
take over the company?

01:14:14.037 --> 01:14:17.210
Are you asking because
you actually want to know

01:14:17.343 --> 01:14:18.680
or are you still working?

01:14:19.348 --> 01:14:20.684
'Cause I wanna know.

01:14:22.922 --> 01:14:24.692
I hope you have
a great Christmas.

01:14:26.596 --> 01:14:27.764
[door creaks]

01:14:29.467 --> 01:14:33.241
[emotional orchestral music]

01:14:43.462 --> 01:14:44.799
Thank you.

01:14:45.299 --> 01:14:46.903
Hey Tim, would you mind

01:14:47.036 --> 01:14:48.606
putting this up on
the bulletin board?

01:14:48.740 --> 01:14:50.109
I'd love that,
thank you, so much.

01:14:50.242 --> 01:14:51.111
Hey Mary.

01:14:52.280 --> 01:14:54.417
Actually, I'm glad
I saw you here.

01:14:54.552 --> 01:14:56.021
Oh yeah?

01:14:56.154 --> 01:14:58.025
Let me guess, you're thrilled
about the story, too?

01:14:58.158 --> 01:14:59.562
Oh, yeah.

01:14:59.695 --> 01:15:02.233
It was a bit clunky,
but got the job done.

01:15:02.366 --> 01:15:04.772
But that's not why
I'm glad I saw you.

01:15:07.076 --> 01:15:08.346
I'm competitive.

01:15:08.479 --> 01:15:10.049
I can be competitive.

01:15:10.182 --> 01:15:13.756
People have told me that, and
I think I might have gotten

01:15:13.890 --> 01:15:16.696
a little carried
away the other night.

01:15:16.829 --> 01:15:18.900
I hope I didn't put
you off towards Blake.

01:15:19.034 --> 01:15:21.672
I was just angry about being
excluded from the interview.

01:15:21.806 --> 01:15:23.843
Oh, it's fine.

01:15:24.545 --> 01:15:26.148
It doesn't matter anyway.

01:15:26.716 --> 01:15:28.653
You were put in an
impossible situation.

01:15:28.786 --> 01:15:30.557
Happens to me all the time.

01:15:31.358 --> 01:15:33.329
Why do you think I was so
difficult to deal with?

01:15:33.462 --> 01:15:34.331
[Mary sighs]

01:15:34.464 --> 01:15:35.466
You weren't difficult.

01:15:35.601 --> 01:15:37.103
You were just doing your job.

01:15:37.805 --> 01:15:39.608
And you were just doing yours.

01:15:40.242 --> 01:15:41.144
Yeah.

01:15:42.515 --> 01:15:45.587
So, what are you gonna do
now that Alton's leaving?

01:15:45.721 --> 01:15:47.056
Blake told me.

01:15:47.925 --> 01:15:50.630
Figure it out, we always do.

01:15:50.764 --> 01:15:52.300
And you will too, right?

01:15:52.433 --> 01:15:54.238
Yeah, yeah, of course.

01:15:54.371 --> 01:15:55.640
[Mary chuckles]

01:15:57.511 --> 01:15:58.746
What are these?

01:15:58.880 --> 01:16:00.349
Oh, my side hustle.

01:16:00.483 --> 01:16:02.286
I'm helping a friend
on the town council

01:16:02.420 --> 01:16:03.990
with her reelection campaign.

01:16:04.124 --> 01:16:05.727
Should be a walk in
the park, though.

01:16:06.428 --> 01:16:08.566
There are more vacancies
than candidates this time.

01:16:08.700 --> 01:16:10.102
- Here.
- Let me see.

01:16:11.271 --> 01:16:12.575
Huh.

01:16:12.708 --> 01:16:14.143
Well, good luck.

01:16:14.277 --> 01:16:15.680
Thanks, Mary.

01:16:17.116 --> 01:16:18.485
Merry Christmas.

01:16:18.620 --> 01:16:19.721
Hey.

01:16:20.790 --> 01:16:22.226
Mary.

01:16:22.359 --> 01:16:23.930
- No.
- Christmas.

01:16:24.064 --> 01:16:25.867
- Yes.
- [Mary giggles]

01:16:26.001 --> 01:16:27.036
- Yes.
- Thank you.

01:16:27.169 --> 01:16:28.507
- You're welcome.
- Merry Christmas.

01:16:28.640 --> 01:16:30.209
[Mary chuckles]

01:16:32.280 --> 01:16:34.952
[soft, bright music]

01:16:41.231 --> 01:16:42.033
Mary.

01:16:42.167 --> 01:16:44.538
What are you doing back here?

01:16:44.672 --> 01:16:46.441
I just need some cheering up.

01:16:46.909 --> 01:16:48.311
[Mary sniffles]

01:16:48.445 --> 01:16:49.715
Is Crash still here?

01:16:49.849 --> 01:16:51.753
He's down in the
basement fixing the boiler.

01:16:51.886 --> 01:16:53.222
That man can't sit still.

01:16:53.355 --> 01:16:54.692
[Mary chuckles]

01:16:54.825 --> 01:16:56.095
I'm not gonna
stay for too long.

01:16:56.228 --> 01:16:58.298
I just wanted to come
by and say hello.

01:16:58.432 --> 01:17:00.335
Did you check the weather?

01:17:00.469 --> 01:17:01.739
No, why?

01:17:01.873 --> 01:17:03.375
Because you're
not going anywhere.

01:17:03.509 --> 01:17:06.080
The storm is supposed
to last until Christmas.

01:17:06.214 --> 01:17:08.351
You'll be stuck on
the highway all night.

01:17:08.986 --> 01:17:10.690
Please tell me
you have a room.

01:17:10.823 --> 01:17:12.226
You can have your room.

01:17:13.429 --> 01:17:14.698
Thanks.

01:17:14.832 --> 01:17:16.401
I wasn't expecting fireworks,

01:17:16.536 --> 01:17:18.405
but I thought you'd be happier.

01:17:18.906 --> 01:17:20.243
No, it's not that.

01:17:20.376 --> 01:17:21.277
It's just--

01:17:22.313 --> 01:17:23.215
Blake?

01:17:24.317 --> 01:17:26.622
Did you see the
Johnson Toy story?

01:17:26.756 --> 01:17:28.258
Everybody saw it.

01:17:29.227 --> 01:17:30.530
Not my best work.

01:17:31.264 --> 01:17:34.972
The shots were nice, you
got the whole town in it,

01:17:35.105 --> 01:17:37.176
and everyone looked
good on camera.

01:17:37.309 --> 01:17:39.347
Oh, you didn't
like it, either.

01:17:40.149 --> 01:17:42.687
It's okay.
But you know what?

01:17:43.388 --> 01:17:44.323
This place,

01:17:45.927 --> 01:17:48.966
my time here, it changed me.

01:17:49.100 --> 01:17:50.571
[tender orchestra music]

01:17:50.704 --> 01:17:52.674
And I went home, it doesn't
feel like home anymore.

01:17:52.808 --> 01:17:54.979
But I messed up, and
now, I don't know

01:17:55.112 --> 01:17:57.449
if there's a place
for me here, either.

01:17:58.787 --> 01:18:00.189
It'll be okay, dear.

01:18:00.322 --> 01:18:02.460
You just need a
good night's sleep.

01:18:02.594 --> 01:18:03.396
Yeah, maybe.

01:18:03.530 --> 01:18:04.799
[Mary chuckles]

01:18:04.932 --> 01:18:06.636
Thanks, Bernice.

01:18:06.769 --> 01:18:08.105
Let's go inside.

01:18:08.238 --> 01:18:09.274
Okay.

01:18:09.407 --> 01:18:10.777
[soft piano music]

01:18:10.911 --> 01:18:11.780
Thank you.

01:18:11.913 --> 01:18:13.415
You're welcome.

01:18:14.116 --> 01:18:17.824
♪<i>♪ Lights on the rooftop ♪</i>

01:18:17.958 --> 01:18:21.665
♪<i>♪ Candles on the table ♪</i>

01:18:21.799 --> 01:18:25.239
